# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: steamboat
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] Launched in 1821, *Aaron Manby* was the first steamship to be built of iron.
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] She was the brainchild of the eccentric but far-seeing naval officer Captain (later Admiral) Charles Napier, who had conceived the idea of a fleet of steamships for service on the River Seine.
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] The ship was named after the master of the Horseley Ironworks, Tipton, Staffordshire, where she was pre-fabricated to a design jointly formulated by Captain Napier, Aaron Manby and his son Charles.
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] She was then shipped in pieces to Rotherhithe on the Thames and assembled there.
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] Of 116 tons burthen, the ship was 120 feet (37 m) long.
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] Her flat-bottomed hull was made of 1⁄4-inch-thick (6.4 mm) iron plate fastened to angle-iron ribs.
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] There was one deck, of wood, and a bowsprit.
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] The ship's distinctive profile boasted a single 47-foot-high (14 m) funnel.
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] The engine was of the oscillating type, designed and patented (British Patent No 4558 of 1821) by Aaron Manby.
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] The paddlewheels: were 12 feet (3.7 m) in diameter but only 2.5 feet (76 cm) wide, because the vessel's maximum beam was limited to 23 feet (7.0 m) for service on the Seine.
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] Defying the prevailing wisdom of the day, the iron-hulled vessel not only floated but made 9 knots (10 mph; 17 km/h) and drew one foot (30 cm) less water than any other steamboat then operating.
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] After trials in May 1822, *Aaron Manby* crossed the English Channel to Le Havre under Napier's command on 10 June, at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h), carrying passengers and freighted with a cargo of linseed and iron castings.
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] The ship proceeded up the Seine to Paris, where she caused a great stir and where she was based for the next decade.
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] This has been claimed (incorrectly) as the first passage from Britain to France by steam ship.
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] There had been shorter crossings by wooden steamers, but Napier's was the first direct steam crossing from London to Paris and the first seagoing voyage by an iron ship anywhere.
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] After some further channel voyages the ship was used for pleasure trips up and down the Seine.
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] The use of iron plates for the hull, in place of wood, was widely copied in shipbuilding during the following decades.
[src:steamboat/aaron-manby] Napier had conceived the ship as a first step towards an iron warship, and in this sense *Aaron Manby* could be considered a direct ancestor of the Royal Navy's first iron frigate, HMS *Warrior*, built the year of Napier's death.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky, Lincoln was raised on the frontier.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was self-educated and became a lawyer, Illinois state legislator, and U.S. representative.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Angered by the Kansas–Nebraska Act of 1854, which opened the territories to slavery, he became a leader of the new Republican Party.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He reached a national audience in the 1858 Senate campaign debates against Stephen A.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election, becoming the first Republican president.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory prompted a majority of the slave states to begin seceding and form the Confederate States.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] A month after Lincoln assumed the presidency, Confederate forces attacked Fort Sumter, starting the Civil War.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] As a moderate Republican, Lincoln had to navigate conflicting political opinions from contentious factions during the war effort.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He closely supervised the Union's strategy and tactics, including the selection of generals and the implementation of a naval blockade of Southern ports.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He suspended the writ of *habeas corpus* in April 1861, an action that Chief Justice Roger Taney found in *Ex parte Merryman* that only Congress could do, and he averted war with Britain by defusing the *Trent* Affair.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 1, 1863, he issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared the slaves in the states "in rebellion" to be free.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 19, 1863, he delivered the Gettysburg Address, which became one of the most famous speeches in American history.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He promoted the Thirteenth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Constitution, which, in 1865, abolished chattel slavery.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Following his re-election in 1864, he sought to heal the war-torn nation through Reconstruction.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] On April 14, 1865, five days after the Confederate surrender at Appomattox, Lincoln was fatally shot by John Wilkes Booth at Ford's Theatre in Washington, D.C., becoming the first U.S. president to be assassinated.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln is remembered as a martyr and a national hero for his wartime leadership and for his efforts to preserve the Union and abolish slavery.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He is consistently ranked in both popular and scholarly polls as among the greatest presidents in American history.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky on February 12, 1809, Abraham Lincoln was raised on Sinking Spring Farm near Hodgenville, Kentucky.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] The captain was killed in a Native American raid in 1786.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] The family settled in Hardin County, Kentucky, in the early 1800s.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nancy is widely assumed to have been the daughter of Lucy Hanks.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy married on June 12, 1806, and moved to Elizabethtown, Kentucky.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] They had three children: Sarah, Abraham, and Thomas Jr., who died as an infant.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's father bought multiple farms in Kentucky but could not get clear property titles to any, losing hundreds of acres in legal disputes.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1816, the family moved to Indiana, where land titles were more reliable.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] They settled on a forested plot in Little Pigeon Creek Community.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Kentucky and Indiana, Thomas worked as a farmer, cabinetmaker, and carpenter.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] At various times, he owned farms, livestock, and town lots, appraised estates, and served on county patrols.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy were members of a Separate Baptist Church, a pious evangelical group whose members largely opposed slavery.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Overcoming financial challenges, Thomas obtained clear title to 80 acres (32 ha) in Little Pigeon Creek Community in 1827.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] On October 5, 1818, Nancy died from milk sickness, leaving 11-year-old Sarah in charge of the household, which included her father, 9-year-old Abraham, and Nancy's 19-year-old orphan cousin, Dennis Hanks.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas married Sarah Bush Johnston, a widow with three children of her own, on December 2, 1819.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became close to his stepmother and called her "Mama".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 20, 1828, Lincoln's sister died in childbirth, devastating him.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] His formal schooling was from itinerant teachers.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] It included two short stints in Kentucky, where he learned to read, but probably not to write.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] After moving to Indiana at age seven, he attended school only sporadically, for a total of less than 12 months by age 15.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nevertheless, he was an avid reader and maintained a lifelong interest in learning.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln was a teenager his father relied heavily on him for farmwork and for supplementary income, hiring the boy out to area farmers and pocketing the money, as was the custom at the time.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] When he was somewhat older, Lincoln and some friends took a job carrying goods by flatboat to New Orleans, Louisiana, where the slave markets, according to the historian Michael Burlingame, "would leave an indelible impression on him....
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In March 1830, fearing another milk-sickness outbreak, several members of the extended Lincoln family, including Abraham, moved west to Illinois and settled in Macon County.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became increasingly distant from Thomas, in part due to his father's lack of interest in education; he would later refuse to attend his father's deathbed or funeral in 1851.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Some historians, such as Michael Burlingame, identify Lincoln's first romantic interest as Ann Rutledge, a young woman also from Kentucky whom he met when he moved to New Salem, Illinois.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lewis Gannett disputes that the evidence supports a romantic relationship between the two.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] David Herbert Donald states that "How that friendship [between Lincoln and Rutledge] developed into a romance cannot be reconstructed from the record".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rutledge died on August 25, 1835, of typhoid fever.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln took her death very hard, sinking into a serious depression and contemplating suicide.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the early 1830s, Lincoln met Mary Owens from Kentucky.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Late in 1836, Lincoln agreed to a match with Owens if she returned to New Salem.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Owens arrived that November and he courted her, but they both had second thoughts.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] On August 16, 1837, he wrote Owens a letter saying he would not blame her if she ended the relationship, and she declined to marry him.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1839, Lincoln met Mary Todd in Springfield, Illinois, and the following year they became engaged.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] She was a daughter of Robert Smith Todd, a wealthy lawyer and businessman in Lexington, Kentucky.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln initially broke off the engagement in early 1841, but the two were reconciled and married on November 4, 1842.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1844, the couple bought a house in Springfield near his law office.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] The marriage was turbulent; Mary was verbally abusive and at times physically violent towards her husband.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] The eldest, Robert Todd Lincoln, was born in 1843, and was the only child to live to maturity.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Edward Baker "Eddie" Lincoln, born in 1846, died February 1, 1850, probably of tuberculosis.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's third son, William Wallace "Willie" Lincoln, was born on December 21, 1850, and died of a fever at the White House on February 20, 1862.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] The youngest, Thomas "Tad" Lincoln, was born on April 4, 1853, and died of edema at age 18 on July 16, 1871.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln loved children, and the Lincolns were not considered to be strict with their own.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] The deaths of Eddie and Willie had profound effects on both parents.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln suffered from "melancholy", a condition now thought to be clinical depression.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1831, Lincoln's father moved the family to a new homestead in Coles County, Illinois, after which Abraham struck out on his own.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He made his home in New Salem, Illinois, for six years.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] During 1831 and 1832, Lincoln worked at a general store in New Salem.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He gained a reputation for strength and courage after winning a wrestling match with the leader of a group of ruffians known as the Clary's Grove boys.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1832, he declared his candidacy for the Illinois House of Representatives, though he interrupted his campaign to serve as a captain in the Illinois Militia during the Black Hawk War.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was elected the captain of his militia company but did not see combat.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his political campaigning, Lincoln advocated for navigational improvements on the Sangamon River.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He drew crowds as a raconteur, but he lacked name recognition, powerful friends, and money, and he lost the election.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln returned home from the war, he planned to become a blacksmith but instead purchased a New Salem general store in partnership with William Berry.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Because a license was required to sell customers alcoholic beverages, Berry obtained bartending licenses for Lincoln and himself, and in 1833 the Lincoln–Berry General Store became a tavern as well.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Burlingame wrote that Berry was "an undisciplined, hard-drinking fellow", and Lincoln "was too soft-hearted to deny anyone credit".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the economy was booming, the business struggled and went into debt, prompting Lincoln to sell his share.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served as New Salem's postmaster and later as county surveyor, but he continued his voracious reading and decided to become a lawyer.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rather than studying in the office of an established attorney, as was customary, Lincoln read law on his own, borrowing legal texts, including Blackstone's *Commentaries* and Chitty's *Pleadings*, from attorney John Todd Stuart.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He later said of his legal education that he "studied with nobody." He was bestowed an honorary degree of Doctor of Laws by Columbia University in 1861.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Lincoln's second state house campaign in 1834, as a supporter of Whig Party leader Henry Clay, he finished second among thirteen candidates running for four places.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln echoed Clay's support for the American Colonization Society, which advocated abolition in conjunction with settling freed slaves in Liberia.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Whigs also favored economic modernization in banking, tariffs to fund internal improvements such as railroads, and urbanization.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served four terms in the Illinois House of Representatives for Sangamon County.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this role, he championed construction of the Illinois and Michigan Canal.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln voted to expand suffrage beyond White landowners to all White men.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the chartering of the Illinois State Bank, and also led a successful campaign for moving the state capital from Vandalia to Springfield.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 27, 1838, Lincoln delivered an address at the Lyceum in Springfield, after the murder of the anti-slavery newspaper editor Elijah Parish Lovejoy.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this ostensibly non-partisan speech, Lincoln attacked Stephen A.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas and the Democratic Party, who the Whigs argued were supporting "mobocracy".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] His speech also attacked anti-abolitionism and racial bigotry.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was criticized in the press for a planned duel with James Shields, whom he had ridiculed in letters published under the name "Aunt Rebecca".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the duel did not take place, Burlingame noted that "the affair embarrassed Lincoln terribly".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1843, Lincoln sought the Whig nomination for Illinois's 7th district seat in the U.S.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Hardin was the winning candidate, though Lincoln convinced the party convention to limit Hardin to one term.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln not only gained the nomination in 1846, but also won the election.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] The only Whig in the Illinois delegation, he was assigned to the Committee on Post Office and Post Roads and the Committee on Expenditures in the War Department.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Giddings on a bill to abolish slavery in the District of Columbia, but dropped the bill when it failed to attract support from most other Whigs.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln spoke against the Mexican–American War (1846–1848), for which he said President James K.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk had "some strong motive ... to involve the two countries in a war, and trusting to escape scrutiny, by fixing the public gaze upon the exceeding brightness of military glory—that attractive rainbow, that rises in showers of blood".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the Wilmot Proviso, a failed 1846 proposal to ban slavery in any U.S. territory won from Mexico.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk insisted that Mexican soldiers had begun the war by "invading the territory of the State of Texas ... and shedding the blood of our citizens on our own soil".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his 1847 "spot resolutions", Lincoln rhetorically demanded that Polk tell Congress the exact "spot" where this occurred, but the Polk administration did not respond.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] His approach and rhetoric cost Lincoln political support in his district, and newspapers derisively nicknamed him "spotty Lincoln".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln had pledged in 1846 to serve only one term in the House.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the 1848 Whig National Convention, he initially supported Henry Clay and was among the leaders of the Illinois delegation backing Clay, voting for him on the early ballots.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] When it became clear that Clay could not secure the nomination, Lincoln joined other Whigs in shifting support to Zachary Taylor, who won the party's nomination and the presidency in 1848.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Taylor won, Lincoln hoped in vain to be appointed commissioner of the United States General Land Office.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] The administration offered to appoint him secretary of the Oregon Territory instead.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] This would have disrupted his legal and political career in Illinois, so he declined and resumed his law practice.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was admitted to the Illinois bar on September 9, 1836.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He moved to Springfield and began to practice law under John T.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He partnered for several years with Stephen T.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Logan and, in 1844, began his practice with William Herndon.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Springfield practice, according to Donald, Lincoln handled "virtually every kind of business that could come before a prairie lawyer".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He dealt with many transportation cases in the midst of the nation's western expansion, particularly river barge conflicts under the new railroad bridges.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1849 he received a patent for a flotation device for the movement of riverboats in shallow water and Lincoln initially favored riverboat legal interests, but he represented whoever hired him.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He represented a bridge company against a riverboat company in *Hurd v.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rock Island Bridge Company*, a landmark case involving a canal boat that sank after hitting a bridge.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] His patent was never commercialized, but it made Lincoln the only president to hold a patent.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln appeared before the Illinois Supreme Court in 411 cases.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] From 1853 to 1860, one of his largest clients was the Illinois Central Railroad, which Lincoln successfully sued to recover his legal fees.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln represented William "Duff" Armstrong in his 1858 trial for the murder of James Preston Metzker.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] The case is famous for Lincoln's use of a fact established by judicial notice to challenge the credibility of an eyewitness.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] After a witness testified to seeing the crime in the moonlight, Lincoln produced a *Farmers' Almanac* showing the Moon was at a low angle, drastically reducing visibility.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In an 1859 murder case, he defended "Peachy" Quinn Harrison, the grandson of Peter Cartwright, Lincoln's political opponent.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Harrison was charged with the murder of Greek Crafton who, according to Cartwright, said as he lay dying that he had "brought it upon myself" and that he forgave Harrison.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln angrily protested the judge's initial decision to exclude Cartwright's claim as hearsay.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln argued that the testimony involved a dying declaration and so was not subject to the hearsay rule.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Instead of holding Lincoln in contempt of court as expected, the judge, a Democrat, admitted the testimony into evidence, resulting in Harrison's acquittal.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Compromise of 1850 failed to alleviate tensions over slavery between the slave-holding South and the free North.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the slavery debate in the Nebraska and Kansas territories became particularly acrimonious, Illinois Senator Stephen A.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas proposed popular sovereignty as a compromise; the measure would allow the electorate of each territory to decide the status of slavery.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] The legislation alarmed many Northerners, who sought to prevent the spread of slavery, but Douglas's Kansas–Nebraska Act narrowly passed Congress in May 1854.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's Peoria Speech of October 1854, in which he declared his opposition to slavery, was one of an estimated 175 speeches he delivered in the next six years on the topic of excluding slavery from the territories.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's attacks on the Kansas–Nebraska Act marked his return to political life.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nationally, the Whigs were irreparably split by the Kansas–Nebraska Act and other ineffective efforts to compromise on the slavery issue.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Reflecting on the demise of his party, Lincoln wrote in 1855, "I think I am a whig; but others say there are no whigs, and that I am an abolitionist....
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] I now do no more than oppose the *extension* of slavery." The new Republican Party was formed as a northern party dedicated to anti-slavery, drawing from the anti-slavery wing of the Whig Party and combining Free Soil, Liberty, and anti-slavery Democratic Party members.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln resisted early Republican entreaties, fearing that the new party would become a platform for extreme abolitionists.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln held out hope for rejuvenating the Whigs, though he lamented his party's growing closeness with the nativist Know Nothing movement.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1854, Lincoln was elected to the Illinois legislature, but before the term began he declined to take his seat so that he would be eligible to run in the upcoming U.S.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] At that time, senators were elected by state legislatures.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] After leading in the first six rounds of voting, Lincoln was unable to obtain a majority.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln instructed his backers to vote for Lyman Trumbull, an anti-slavery Democrat who had received few votes in the earlier ballots.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's decision to withdraw enabled his Whig supporters and Trumbull's anti-slavery Democrats to combine and defeat the mainstream Democratic candidate, Joel Aldrich Matteson.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Violent political confrontations in Kansas continued, and opposition to the Kansas–Nebraska Act remained strong throughout the North.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the 1856 elections approached, Lincoln joined the Republicans and attended the Bloomington Convention, where the Illinois Republican Party was established.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] The convention platform endorsed Congress's right to regulate slavery in the territories and backed the admission of Kansas as a free state.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln gave the final speech of the convention, calling for the preservation of the Union.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the June 1856 Republican National Convention, Lincoln received support to run as vice president, but the party put forward a ticket of John C.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Frémont and William Dayton, which Lincoln supported throughout Illinois.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Democrats nominated James Buchanan and the Know Nothings nominated Millard Fillmore.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Buchanan prevailed, while Republican William Henry Bissell won election as Governor of Illinois, and Lincoln became a leading Republican in Illinois.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Dred Scott was a slave whose master took him from a slave state to a territory that was free as a result of the Missouri Compromise.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Scott was returned to the slave state, he petitioned a federal court for his freedom.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] His petition was denied in *Dred Scott v.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Taney wrote in his opinion that the Missouri Compromise was unconstitutional because it infringed on slave owners' property rights by prohibiting them from bringing their slaves into the territories.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] While many Democrats hoped that *Dred Scott* would end the dispute over slavery in the territories, the decision sparked further outrage in the North.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln denounced it as the product of a conspiracy of Democrats to support the Slave Power.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He argued that the decision was at variance with the Declaration of Independence, which stated that "all men are created equal ... with certain unalienable rights", among them "life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1858, Douglas was up for re-election in the U.S.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Senate, and Lincoln hoped to defeat him.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the party felt that a former Whig should be nominated in 1858, and Lincoln's 1856 campaigning and support of Trumbull had earned him a favor.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] For the first time, Illinois Republicans held a convention to agree upon a Senate candidate, and Lincoln won the nomination with little opposition.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln accepted the nomination with great enthusiasm and zeal.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] The speech created a stark image of the danger of disunion.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Senate campaign featured seven debates between Lincoln and Douglas; they had an atmosphere akin to a prizefight and drew thousands.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln warned that the Slave Power was threatening the values of republicanism, and he accused Douglas of distorting Jefferson's premise that all men are created equal.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Freeport Doctrine, Douglas argued that, despite the *Dred Scott* decision, which he claimed to support, local settlers, under popular sovereignty, should be free to choose whether to allow slavery in their territory.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He accused Lincoln of having joined the abolitionists.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though the Republican legislative candidates won more popular votes, the Democrats won more seats, and the legislature re-elected Douglas.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] However, Lincoln's articulation of the issues had given him a national political presence.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the aftermath of the 1858 election, newspapers frequently mentioned Lincoln as a potential Republican presidential candidate.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] While Lincoln was popular in the Midwest, he lacked support in the Northeast and was unsure whether to seek the office.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In January 1860, Lincoln told a group of political allies that he would accept the presidential nomination if offered and, in the following months, William O.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Stoddard's *Central Illinois Gazette*, the *Chicago Press & Tribune*, and other local papers endorsed his candidacy.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In February 1860, Henry Ward Beecher invited Lincoln to address his congregation at Plymouth Church in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln agreed, but the venue shifted to Cooper Union in Manhattan.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the audience thought he appeared awkward and even ugly.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] But Lincoln demonstrated intellectual leadership, which brought him into contention for the presidency.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Journalist Noah Brooks reported, "No man ever before made such an impression on his first appeal to a New York audience".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Historian David Herbert Donald described the speech as "a superb political move for an unannounced presidential aspirant." In response to an inquiry about his ambitions, Lincoln said, "The taste *is* in my mouth a little".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 9–10, 1860, the Illinois Republican State Convention was held in Decatur.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Exploiting his embellished frontier legend of clearing land and splitting fence rails, Lincoln's supporters promoted him as "The Rail Candidate".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 18 at the Republican National Convention in Chicago, Lincoln won the nomination on the third ballot.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] A former Democrat, Hannibal Hamlin of Maine, was nominated for vice president to balance the ticket.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Throughout the 1850s, Lincoln had doubted the prospects of civil war, and his supporters rejected claims that his election would incite secession.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Douglas was selected as the candidate of the Northern Democrats, delegates from the Southern slave states elected incumbent Vice President John C.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] A group of former Whigs and Know Nothings formed the Constitutional Union Party and nominated John Bell of Tennessee.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln and Douglas competed for votes in the North, while Bell and Breckinridge found support primarily in the South.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] A nationwide militaristic Republican youth organization, the Wide Awakes, "turned it into one of the most excited elections in American history" and "triggered massive popular enthusiasm", according to the political historian Jon Grinspan.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] People of the Northern states knew the Southern states would vote against Lincoln and rallied supporters for him.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] As Douglas and the other candidates campaigned, Lincoln gave no speeches, relying on the enthusiasm of the Republican Party.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Republican speakers emphasized Lincoln's childhood poverty to demonstrate the power of "free labor", which allowed a common farm boy to work his way to the top by his own efforts.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though he did not make public appearances, many sought to visit and write to Lincoln.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the runup to the election, he took an office in the Illinois state capitol to deal with the influx of attention.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] He also hired John George Nicolay as his personal secretary, who would remain in that role during the presidency.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 6, 1860, Lincoln was elected as the first Republican president.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory was entirely due to his support in the North and West.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] No ballots were cast for him in 10 of the 15 Southern slave states.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln received 1,866,452 votes, or 39.8 percent of the total in a four-way race, carrying the free Northern states, as well as California and Oregon, and winning the electoral vote decisively.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] above the rotunda still under construction.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] following Lincoln's first inauguration portended imminent hostilities.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Lincoln's election, secessionists implemented plans to leave the Union before he took office in March 1861.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] On December 20, 1860, South Carolina adopted an ordinance of secession; by February 1, 1861, Florida, Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas had followed.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Six of these states declared themselves to be a sovereign nation, the Confederate States of America, selecting Jefferson Davis as its provisional president.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The upper South and border states (Delaware, Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky, Missouri, and Arkansas) initially rejected the secessionist appeal.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] President Buchanan and President-elect Lincoln refused to recognize the Confederacy, declaring secession illegal.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 11, 1861, Lincoln gave a particularly emotional farewell address upon leaving Springfield for Washington.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and the Republicans rejected the proposed Crittenden Compromise as contrary to the party's platform of free-soil in the territories.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln said, "I will suffer death before I consent ... to any concession or compromise which looks like buying the privilege to take possession of this government to which we have a constitutional right".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln supported the Corwin Amendment to the U.S.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Constitution, which would have protected slavery in states where it already existed.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The amendment passed Congress and was awaiting ratification by the required three-fourths of the states when Southern states began to secede.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] On March 4, 1861, in his first inaugural address, Lincoln said that, because he held "such a provision to now be implied constitutional law, I have no objection to its being made express, and irrevocable".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Due to secessionist plots, careful attention was paid to Lincoln's security and the train he took to Washington.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president-elect evaded suspected assassins in Baltimore.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] He traveled in disguise, wearing a soft felt hat instead of his customary stovepipe hat and draping an overcoat over his shoulders while hunching to conceal his height.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 23, 1861, he arrived in Washington, D.C., which was placed under military guard.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many in the opposition press criticized his secretive journey; opposition newspapers mocked Lincoln with caricatures showing him sneaking into the capital.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president ended his address with an appeal to the people of the South: "We are not enemies, but friends....
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The mystic chords of memory, stretching from every battle-field, and patriot grave, to every living heart and hearthstone ... will yet swell the chorus of the Union, when again touched ... by the better angels of our nature".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Donald, the failure of the Peace Conference of 1861 to attract the attendance of seven of the Confederate states signaled that legislative compromise was not a practical expectation.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In selecting his cabinet, Lincoln chose the men he found the most competent, even when they had been his opponents for the presidency.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln commented on his thought process, "We need the strongest men of the party in the Cabinet.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] We needed to hold our own people together.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] I had looked the party over and concluded that these were the very strongest men.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Then I had no right to deprive the country of their services." Doris Kearns Goodwin described the group in her 2005 biography of Lincoln as a "team of rivals".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln named his main political opponent, William H.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln made five appointments to the Supreme Court.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Noah Haynes Swayne, a prominent corporate lawyer from Ohio, replaced John McLean after the latter's death in April 1861.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Samuel Freeman Miller, who replaced Peter V.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Daniel, was an avowed abolitionist and received widespread support from Iowa politicians.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] David Davis was Lincoln's campaign manager in 1860 and had served as a judge in the Illinois court circuit where Lincoln practiced.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democrat Stephen Johnson Field, a previous California Supreme Court justice, provided geographic and political balance.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Taney, Lincoln appointed his former secretary of the treasury, Salmon P.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Chase, to replace Taney as chief justice.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln believed Chase was an able jurist who would support Reconstruction legislation and that his appointment would unite the Republican Party.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April 1861, Major Robert Anderson, commander of Fort Sumter in Charleston, South Carolina, advised that he was nearly out of food.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] After considerable deliberation, Lincoln decided to send provisions; according to Michael Burlingame, he "could not be sure that his decision would precipitate a war, though he had good reason to believe that it might".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 12, 1861, Confederate forces fired on Union troops at Fort Sumter, starting the American Civil War.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The April 12 and 13 attack on Fort Sumter rallied the Northern public to see military action against the South as necessary to defend the nation.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 15, Lincoln called for 75,000 militiamen to recapture forts, protect Washington, and preserve the Union.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] This call forced states to choose whether to secede or to support the Union.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] North Carolina, Virginia, Tennessee, and Arkansas seceded.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the Northern states sent regiments south, on April 19 Baltimore mobs in control of the rail links attacked Union troops who were changing trains.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Local leaders' groups later burned critical rail bridges to the capital and the Army responded by arresting local Maryland officials.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln suspended the writ of *habeas corpus*, allowing arrests without formal charges.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Merryman, a Maryland officer arrested for hindering U.S. troop movements, successfully petitioned Supreme Court Chief Justice Taney to issue a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In an opinion titled *Ex parte Merryman*, Taney, not ruling on behalf of the Supreme Court, wrote that the Constitution authorized only Congress and not the president to suspend habeas corpus.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] But Lincoln engaged in nonacquiescence and persisted with the policy of suspension in select areas.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Under various suspensions, 15,000 civilians were detained without trial; several, including the anti-war Democrat Clement L.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Vallandigham, were tried in military courts for "treasonable" actions, which was condemned as an attack on free speech.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln took executive control of the war and shaped the Union military strategy.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] He responded to the unprecedented political and military crisis as commander-in-chief by exercising unprecedented authority.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] He expanded his war powers, imposed a naval blockade on Confederate ports, disbursed funds before appropriation by Congress, suspended *habeas corpus*, and arrested and imprisoned thousands of suspected Confederate sympathizers.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gained the support of Congress and the northern public for these actions.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also had to reinforce Union sympathies in the border slave states and keep the war from becoming an international conflict.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was clear from the outset that bipartisan support was essential to success, and that any compromise alienated factions in both political parties.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Copperheads (anti-war Democrats) criticized Lincoln for refusing to compromise on slavery; the Radical Republicans, who demanded harsh treatment against secession, criticized him for moving too slowly to abolish slavery.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] On August 6, 1861, Lincoln signed the Confiscation Act, which authorized judicial proceedings to confiscate and free slaves who were used to support the Confederates.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law had little practical effect, but it signaled political support for abolishing slavery.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's war strategy had two priorities: ensuring that Washington was well defended and conducting an aggressive war effort for a prompt, decisive victory.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Twice a week, Lincoln met with his cabinet.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Occasionally, Lincoln's wife, Mary, prevailed on him to take a carriage ride, concerned that he was working too hard.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, Lincoln selected civilian generals from varied political and ethnic backgrounds "to secure their and their constituents' support for the war effort and ensure that the war became a national struggle".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In January 1862, after complaints of inefficiency and profiteering in the War Department, Lincoln replaced Simon Cameron as secretary of war with Edwin Stanton.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stanton worked more often and more closely with Lincoln than did any other senior official.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Stanton's biographers Benjamin P.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Thomas and Harold Hyman, "Stanton and Lincoln virtually conducted the war together".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln saw the importance of Vicksburg for control of the Mississippi River valley and understood the necessity of defeating the enemy's army, rather than merely capturing territory.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In directing the Union's war strategy, Lincoln valued the advice of Winfield Scott, even after his retirement as Commanding General of the United States Army.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1861 Scott proposed the Anaconda Plan, which relied on port blockades and advancing down the Mississippi to subdue the South.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In June 1862, Lincoln made an unannounced visit to West Point, where he spent five hours consulting with Scott regarding the handling of the war.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Internationally, Lincoln wanted to forestall foreign military aid to the Confederacy.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] He relied on his combative Secretary of State William Seward while working closely with Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman Charles Sumner.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Navy illegally intercepted a British mail ship, the *RMS Trent*, on the high seas and seized two Confederate envoys.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although the North celebrated the seizure, Britain protested vehemently, and the Trent Affair threatened war between the Americans and the British.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ended the crisis by releasing the two diplomats.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union rout at Bull Run and Winfield Scott's retirement, Lincoln appointed George B.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, McClellan created defenses for Washington that were almost impregnable: 48 forts and batteries, with 480 guns manned by 7,200 artillerists.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] He spent months planning his Virginia Peninsula Campaign.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan's slow progress and excessive precautions frustrated Lincoln.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan, in turn, blamed the failure of the campaign on Lincoln's cautiousness in having reserved troops for the capital.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1862, Lincoln removed McClellan as general-in-chief; he elevated Henry Halleck to the post and appointed John Pope as head of the new Army of Virginia.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the summer of 1862 Pope was soundly defeated at the Second Battle of Bull Run, forcing him to retreat to Washington.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Soon after, the Army of Virginia was disbanded.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite his dissatisfaction with McClellan's failure to reinforce Pope, Lincoln restored him to command of all forces around Washington, which included both the Army of the Potomac and the remains of the Army of Virginia.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's forces crossed the Potomac River into Maryland, leading to the Battle of Antietam.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] This battle, a Union victory, was among the bloodiest in American history.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] A crisis of command occurred for Lincoln when McClellan then resisted the president's demand that he pursue Lee's withdrawing army, while Don Carlos Buell likewise refused orders to move the Army of the Ohio against rebel forces in eastern Tennessee.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln replaced Buell with William Rosecrans and McClellan with Ambrose Burnside; according to Donald, this was a "shrewd" political move as they were non-partisan—unlike McClellan, a Democrat.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Against presidential advice, Burnside launched an offensive across the Rappahannock River and was defeated by Lee at Fredericksburg in December.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Facing low morale and discontent among the troops, Lincoln replaced Burnside with Joseph Hooker.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hooker endured heavy casualties at the Battle of Chancellorsville in May, then resigned in June and was replaced by George Meade.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Meade followed Lee north into Pennsylvania and defeated him in the Gettysburg campaign but then failed to effectively block Lee's orderly retreat to Virginia, despite Lincoln's demands.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant captured Vicksburg and gained control of the Mississippi River.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In May 1863, Lincoln issued the Lieber Code, which governed wartime conduct of the Union Army, defining command responsibility for war crimes and crimes against humanity.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two Union generals had issued emancipation orders in 1861 and 1862, but Lincoln overrode both: he found that the decision to emancipate was not within the generals' power, and that it might induce loyal border states to secede.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, in June 1862, Congress passed an act banning slavery in all federal territories, which Lincoln signed.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In July, the Confiscation Act of 1862 was enacted, allowing the seizure of slaves from those disloyal to the United States.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] On July 22, 1862, Lincoln reviewed a draft of the Emancipation Proclamation with his cabinet.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Senator Willard Saulsbury Sr. criticized the proclamation, stating that it "would light their author to dishonor through all future generations".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] By contrast, Horace Greeley, editor of the *New-York Tribune*, in his public letter, "The Prayer of Twenty Millions", implored Lincoln to embrace emancipation.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Buttressed by news of the recent Union victory at Antietam, on September 22, 1862, Lincoln issued the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, which proclaimed that, on January 1, 1863, all persons held as slaves within any state still in rebellion would be free.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] On January 1, 1863, he issued the final Emancipation Proclamation, freeing the slaves in the ten states not then under Union control, exempting areas under such control.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] With the abolition of slavery in the rebel states now a military objective, Union armies advancing south enabled thousands to escape bondage.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Proclamation was immediately denounced by Copperheads, who advocated restoring the union by allowing slavery.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was also seen as a betrayal of his promise to Southern Unionists not to tamper with slavery; Emerson Etheridge, then Clerk of the House of Representatives, joined an unsuccessful plot to give the Democrats and Southern Unionists control of the House.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a result of the Proclamation, enlisting freedmen became official policy.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In a letter to Tennessee military governor Andrew Johnson, Lincoln wrote, "The bare sight of fifty thousand armed, and drilled black soldiers on the banks of the Mississippi would end the rebellion at once".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gave the dedication for the Gettysburg battlefield cemetery on November 19, 1863.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The address became the most quoted speech in American history.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Following Admiral David Farragut's capture of New Orleans in 1862, and after victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg, Lincoln proclaimed a national Thanksgiving holiday, to be celebrated on the final Thursday of November 1863.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's victories at the Battle of Shiloh and in the Vicksburg campaign impressed Lincoln.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Responding to criticism of Grant after Shiloh, Lincoln said, "I can't spare this man.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] He fights." Following Meade's failure to capture Lee's army after Gettysburg and after Grant's success at Chattanooga, Lincoln promoted Grant to commander of all Union armies.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln reacted to Union losses by mobilizing support throughout the North.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union forces targeted infrastructure—plantations, railroads, and bridges—to weaken the South's morale and fighting ability.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] While Lincoln sanctioned this approach, he emphasized the defeat of the Confederate armies over destruction for its own sake.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody Overland Campaign turned into a strategic success for the Union despite a number of setbacks.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] But the campaign was the bloodiest in American history: approximately 55,000 casualties on the Union side (including 7,600 deaths), compared to about 33,000 on the Confederate (including 4,200 deaths).
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's losses, although lower in absolute numbers, were proportionately higher (over 50%) than Grant's (about 45%).
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April, the Confederate government evacuated Richmond and Lincoln visited the conquered capital.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Amid the turmoil of military actions, on June 30, 1864, Lincoln signed into law the Yosemite Grant, which provided unprecedented federal protection for the area now known as Yosemite National Park.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and Secretary of the Treasury Salmon Chase faced a challenge in funding a wartime economy.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress quickly approved Lincoln's request to assemble an army, even increasing his proposed 400,000 soldiers to 500,000, but both Congress and Chase initially resisted raising taxes.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union defeat at the First Battle of Bull Run, which collapsed the bond market, Congress passed the Revenue Act of 1861.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] This act imposed the first U.S. federal income tax, creating a flat tax of three percent on annual incomes above $800 ($28,700 in current dollars).
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the average urban worker made approximately $600 per year, many were not required to pay income taxes.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also signed increases to the Morrill Tariff, which had become law in the final months of Buchanan's tenure.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] These tariffs raised import duties considerably and were designed both to increase revenue and to help manufacturers offset the burden of new taxes.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Throughout the war, Congress debated whether to raise additional revenue primarily by increasing tariff rates, which most strongly affected rural areas, or by increasing income taxes, which most affected wealthier individuals; the latter view proved more popular.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The revenue measures of 1861 proved inadequate for funding the war, forcing Congress to take further action.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In February 1862, Congress passed the Legal Tender Act, which authorized the minting of $150 million in "greenbacks"—the first banknotes issued by the U.S. government since the end of the American Revolution.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Greenbacks were not backed by gold or silver, but rather by the government's promise to honor their value.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, $450 million worth of greenbacks were in circulation.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress also passed the Revenue Act of 1862, which established an excise tax affecting nearly every commodity, as well as the first national inheritance tax.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] It also added a progressive tax structure to the federal income tax.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] To collect these taxes, Congress created the Office of the Commissioner of Internal Revenue.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite the new revenue measures, funding the war remained challenging.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The government continued to issue greenbacks and borrow large amounts of money, and the U.S. national debt grew from $65 million in 1860 to over $2 billion in 1866.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Revenue Act of 1864 represented a compromise between those who favored a more progressive tax structure and those who favored a flat tax.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] It established a five-percent tax on incomes above $600 and a ten-percent tax on incomes above $10,000, and it raised taxes on businesses.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early 1865, Congress reduced the threshold for ten-percent taxation to incomes above $5000.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, the income tax constituted about one-fifth of the federal government's revenue, though it was intended as a temporary wartime measure.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also took action against wartime fraud, signing into law the False Claims Act of 1863.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] This statute imposed penalties for false claims and made it possible for private citizens to file false-claim (*qui tam*) lawsuits on behalf of the U.S. government and share in the recovery.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hoping to stabilize the currency, Lincoln convinced Congress to pass the National Banking Act in 1863, established the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency to oversee "national banks," which were subject to federal, rather than state, regulation.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In return for investing a third of their capital in federal bonds, national banks were authorized to issue federal banknotes.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Congress imposed a tax on private banknotes in March 1865, federal banknotes became the dominant form of paper currency.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Other economic policies passed under Lincoln included the 1862 Homestead Act, which made millions of acres of government-held land in the West available for purchase at low cost.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The 1862 Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act provided government grants for agricultural colleges in each state.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Pacific Railway Acts of 1862 and 1864 granted federal support for the construction of the United States' first transcontinental railroad, which was completed in 1869.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the start of the war, Russia was the lone great power to support the Union, while the other European powers had varying degrees of sympathy for the Confederacy.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to the historian Dean Mahin, Lincoln had "limited familiarity with diplomatic practices" but exerted "substantial influence on U.S. diplomacy" as the Union attempted to avoid war with Britain and France.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln appointed diplomats to try to persuade European nations not to recognize the Confederacy.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policy succeeded: all foreign nations were officially neutral throughout the Civil War, with none recognizing the Confederacy.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some European leaders looked for ways to exploit the inability of the U.S. to enforce the Monroe Doctrine opposing European colonial intervention in the Americas: Spain invaded the Dominican Republic in 1861, while France established a puppet regime in Mexico.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, many in Europe also hoped for a quick end to the war, both for humanitarian reasons and because of the economic disruption it caused.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed", according to Don H.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union diplomats initially had to explain that the United States was not committed to ending slavery, and instead they argued that secession was unconstitutional.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Confederate spokesmen were more successful by ignoring slavery and instead focusing on their struggle for independence, their commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Confederacy's hope that cotton exports would compel European interference did not come to fruition, as Britain found alternative sources and maintained economic ties with the Union.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Though the issuance of the Emancipation Proclamation in January 1863 did not immediately end the possibility of European intervention, it rallied European public opinion to the Union by adding abolition as a Union war goal.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Any chance of a European intervention in the war ended with the Union victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg in July 1863, as European leaders came to believe that the Confederate cause was doomed.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Dole as commissioner of the Bureau of Indian Affairs and made "extensive use of Indian Service positions to reward political supporters", according to the historian Thomas Britten.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policies largely focused on assimilation of Native Americans and diminishing tribal landholdings, consistent with those of his predecessors, but his direct involvement in Native American affairs was unclear.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] His administration faced difficulties guarding Western settlers, railroads, and telegraph lines from Native American attacks.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Tensions arose with the Dakota people due to American treaty violations, unfair trading, and government practices that led to starvation.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In August 1862, the Dakota War broke out in Minnesota.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hundreds of settlers were killed and 30,000 were displaced from their homes.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some feared incorrectly that it might represent a Confederate conspiracy to start a war on the Northwestern frontier.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ordered thousands of paroled prisoners of war be sent to put down the uprising.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] When the Confederacy protested, Lincoln revoked the policy and none arrived in Minnesota.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln sent Pope as commander of the new Department of the Northwest.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Appointed as a state militia colonel, Henry Hastings Sibley eventually defeated the Dakota chief Little Crow at the Battle of Wood Lake.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] A war crimes trial led by Sibley sentenced 303 Dakota warriors to death; the legal scholar Carol Chomsky described the trial as "a study in military injustice" designed to "guarantee an unjust outcome".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln pardoned all but 39 of the condemned warriors, and, with one execution suspended, the remaining 38 were hanged in the largest mass execution in U.S. history.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congressman Alexander Ramsey told Lincoln in 1864 that he would have received more re-election support in Minnesota had he executed all 303 warriors.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln responded, "I could not afford to hang men for votes." Lincoln called for reform of federal Indian policy but prioritized the war and Reconstruction.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Changes were made in response to the Sand Creek Massacre of November 1864, prioritizing peaceful administration of Native affairs and condemning those encroaching on Native territory, but not until after Lincoln's death.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ran for re-election in 1864; the Democratic nominee was former general McClellan.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Republican Party selected Andrew Johnson, a War Democrat, as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] To broaden his coalition to include War Democrats as well as Republicans, Lincoln ran under the new label of the National Union Party.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody stalemates and Confederate victories such as the Battle of the Crater damaged Lincoln's re-election prospects, and many Republicans feared defeat.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln prepared a confidential memorandum pledging that, if he should lose the election, he would "co-operate with the President-elect, as to save the Union between the election and the inauguration; as he will have secured his election on such ground that he cannot possibly save it afterwards".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Victories at Atlanta in September and in the Shenandoah Valley in October turned public opinion, and Lincoln was re-elected with 55.1 percent of the popular vote as well as 212 electoral votes to McClellan's 21.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Grant continued to weaken Lee's forces, efforts to discuss peace began.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephens, the Confederate vice president, and two other Confederate officials met with Lincoln and Seward at Hampton Roads.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln refused to negotiate with the Confederacy as a coequal, and the only agreement reached at the meeting concerned the exchange of prisoners.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's second inauguration took place on March 4, 1865; historian Mark Noll places his second inaugural address "among the small handful of semi-sacred texts by which Americans conceive their place in the world"; it is inscribed in the Lincoln Memorial.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] A month later, on April 9, Lee surrendered to Grant at Appomattox, signaling the end of the war.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] It triggered a series of subsequent surrenders across the South—in North Carolina, Alabama, and the trans-Mississippi Theater—and finally at sea with the surrender of the CSS *Shenandoah* in November 1865.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Reconstruction began before the war's end, as Lincoln and his associates considered the reintegration of the nation, and the fates of Confederate leaders and freed slaves.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] When a general asked Lincoln how the defeated Confederates were to be treated, Lincoln replied, "Let 'em up easy"; he focused not on blame for the war but on rebuilding.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Determined to reunite the nation and not alienate the South, Lincoln urged that speedy elections under generous terms be held.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] His Amnesty Proclamation of December 8, 1863, offered pardons to those who had not held a Confederate civil office and had not mistreated Union prisoners, if they signed an oath of allegiance.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln led the moderates in Reconstruction policy and was opposed by the Radicals, under Thaddeus Stevens, Charles Sumner and Benjamin Wade, who otherwise remained Lincoln's allies.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Southern states fell, they needed leaders while their administrations were being restored.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Tennessee and Arkansas, Lincoln appointed Andrew Johnson and Frederick Steele, respectively, as military governors.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Louisiana, Lincoln ordered Nathaniel P.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Banks to promote a plan that would reestablish statehood when 10 percent of the voters agreed, but only if the reconstructed states abolished slavery.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democratic opponents accused Lincoln of using the plan to ensure his and the Republicans' political aspirations.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals denounced his policy as too lenient and passed their own plan, the 1864 Wade–Davis Bill, but Lincoln pocket-vetoed it.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals retaliated by refusing to seat elected representatives from Louisiana, Arkansas, and Tennessee.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] After implementing the Emancipation Proclamation, Lincoln increased pressure on Congress to outlaw slavery nationwide with a constitutional amendment.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] By December 1863 an amendment was brought to Congress.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Senate passed it on April 8, 1864, but the first vote in the House of Representatives fell short of the required two-thirds majority.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Passage became part of Lincoln's re-election platform, and after his re-election, the second attempt in the House passed on January 31, 1865.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] After ratification by three-fourths of the states in December 1865, it became the Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution, abolishing "slavery [and] involuntary servitude, except as a punishment for crime".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln announced a Reconstruction plan that involved short-term military administration, pending readmission under the control of southern Unionists.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] He also signed Senator Charles Sumner's Freedmen's Bureau bill that set up a temporary federal agency designed to meet the immediate needs of former slaves.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law opened land for a lease of three years with the ability for the freedmen to purchase title.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Eric Foner argues that "Lincoln did not see Reconstruction as an opportunity for a sweeping political and social revolution beyond emancipation.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] He had long made clear his opposition to the confiscation and redistribution of land." However, the Lincoln scholar Phillip S.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Paludan suggests that at the end of his life Lincoln was moving towards a more radical position, particularly with regards to freedmen's rights.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Wilkes Booth was a well-known actor and a Confederate spy from Maryland; although he never joined the Confederate army, he had contacts within the Confederate secret service.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] After attending Lincoln's last public address, on April 11, 1865, in which Lincoln stated his preference that the franchise be conferred on some Black men, specifically "on the very intelligent, and on those who serve our cause as soldiers", Booth plotted to assassinate the President.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] When Booth learned of the Lincolns' intent to attend a play with Grant, he planned to assassinate Lincoln and Grant at Ford's Theatre.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and his wife attended the play *Our American Cousin* on the evening of April 14.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the last minute, Grant decided to go to New Jersey to visit his children instead.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] At 10:15 pm, Booth entered Lincoln's theater box, crept up from behind, and fired at the back of Lincoln's head, mortally wounding him.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's guest, Major Henry Rathbone, momentarily grappled with Booth, but Booth stabbed him and escaped.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] After being attended by Charles Leale and two other doctors, Lincoln was taken across the street to Petersen House.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] He remained in a coma for nine hours and died at 7:22 am on April 15.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was wrapped in a flag and placed in a coffin, which was loaded into a hearse and escorted to the White House by Union soldiers.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Johnson was sworn in as president later that day.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two weeks later, Booth was located, shot, and killed at a farm in Virginia by Sergeant Boston Corbett.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] From April 19 to 20, Lincoln lay in state, first in the White House and then in the Capitol rotunda.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The caskets containing Lincoln's body and the body of his third son Willie then traveled for two weeks on a funeral train following a circuitous route from Washington D.C. to Springfield, Illinois, stopping at several cities for memorials attended by hundreds of thousands.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many others gathered along the tracks as the train passed with bands, bonfires, and hymn singing or in silent grief.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Historians emphasized the widespread shock and sorrow, but noted that some who had hated Lincoln celebrated his death.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Walt Whitman composed four elegies to Lincoln, including "When Lilacs Last in the Dooryard Bloom'd" and "O Captain!
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was buried at Oak Ridge Cemetery in Springfield and now lies within the Lincoln Tomb.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln redefined the political philosophy of republicanism in the United States.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Because the Declaration of Independence says that all men have an unalienable right to life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness, he called it the "sheet anchor" of republicanism, at a time when the Constitution was the focus of most political discourse.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] He presented the Declaration as establishing equality as a foundational principle for the United States, which had a significant impact on social and political movements in the U.S. into the 20th century.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a Whig activist, Lincoln was a spokesman for business interests, favoring high tariffs, banks, infrastructure improvements, and railroads, in opposition to Jacksonian democrats.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Nevertheless, Lincoln admired Andrew Jackson's steeliness and patriotism, and adopted the Jacksonian "belief in the common man".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a young man, Lincoln was a religious skeptic.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, he was deeply familiar with the Bible; throughout his public career, he often quoted scripture.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] His three most famous speeches—the House Divided Speech, the Gettysburg Address, and his second inaugural address—all contain such quotes.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the 1840s, Lincoln subscribed to the Doctrine of Necessity, a belief that the human mind was controlled by a higher power.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the death of his son Edward in 1850, Lincoln more frequently expressed a dependence on God.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] He never joined a church, although he and his wife frequently attended First Presbyterian Church in Springfield, Illinois, beginning in 1852.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] While president, Lincoln often attended services at the New York Avenue Presbyterian Church in Washington, D.C.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] The death of his son Willie in February 1862 may have caused him to look toward religion for solace.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's frequent use of religious imagery and language toward the end of his life may have reflected his own personal beliefs or might have been a device to reach his audiences, who were mostly evangelical Protestants.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Sources differ in how they describe his religious beliefs.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephen Mansfield describes "an atheist or religiously skeptical Lincoln" as "the prevailing view", although he argues that "there was a spiritual journey of some kind in Abraham Lincoln's life".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Richard Carwardine writes that "Many elements of the inner Lincoln, including his personal faith ... necessarily remain a puzzle".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's last words were, as reported by his wife, "There is no place I so much desire to see as Jerusalem".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Michael Burlingame, Lincoln was described as "awkward" and "gawky" as a youth.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] In adolescence he was tall and strong, participating in jumping, throwing, wrestling, and footraces, and demonstrating exceptional strength.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Burlingame notes that Lincoln's clothes "were typically rough and suited to the frontier", with a gap between his shoes, socks, and pants that often exposed six or more inches of his shin; "he cared little about fashion".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln was a slender six feet four inches, with a high-pitched voice.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] While he is usually portrayed bearded, he did not grow a beard until 1860 at the suggestion of 11-year-old Grace Bedell; he was the first U.S. president to do so.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Herndon described Lincoln's face as "long, narrow, sallow, and cadaverous", his cheeks as "leathery and saffron-colored".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln described himself as having a "dark complexion, with coarse black hair".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although Lincoln's features were said to be "unpleasant to behold," Walt Whitman "wrote that Lincoln's face was 'so awful ugly it becomes beautiful.'" Lincoln's detractors also remarked on his appearance.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Among the illnesses that Lincoln is either documented or speculated to have suffered from are depression, smallpox, and malaria.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] He took blue mass pills, which contained mercury, to treat melancholy or hypochondriasis; this could have resulted in mercury poisoning.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] Several claims have been made that Lincoln's health was declining before his assassination, as photographs of Lincoln appear to show weight loss and facial changes.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p02] It has been proposed that he could have had a rare genetic disorder such as Marfan syndrome or multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2B.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] In surveys of U.S. scholars ranking presidents since 1948, the top three presidents are generally Lincoln, George Washington, and Franklin D.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] A 2004 study found that scholars in history and politics ranked Lincoln number one, while legal scholars placed him second after Washington.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] Kennedy, and Ronald Reagan were the top-ranked presidents in eight public opinion surveys by Gallup.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's assassination made him a national martyr.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] He was viewed by abolitionists as a champion of human liberty.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] Many, though not all, in the South considered Lincoln to be a man of outstanding ability.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] In the New Deal era, liberals honored Lincoln as an advocate of the common man who they claimed would have supported the welfare state, and Lincoln became a favorite of liberal intellectuals across the world.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] The high point came in 1922 with the dedication of the Lincoln Memorial on the National Mall in Washington, D.C.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Black orator and former slave Frederick Douglass stated that in "his company, I was never reminded of my humble origin, or of my unpopular color", and Lincoln has long been known as the Great Emancipator.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] By the late 1960s, some Black intellectuals denied that Lincoln deserved that title.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lerone Bennett Jr. won wide attention when he called Lincoln a White supremacist in 1968.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] He noted that Lincoln used ethnic slurs and argued that Lincoln opposed social equality and proposed that freed slaves voluntarily move to another country.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] Defenders of Lincoln highlighted his condemnation of slavery and his contributions to its abolition, casting his delays and racist rhetoric as concessions to political necessity rather than reflections of his personal beliefs.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has also been characterized as a folk hero and as "Honest Abe".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] David Herbert Donald opined in his 1996 biography that Lincoln was endowed with the personality trait of negative capability, attributed to extraordinary leaders who were "capable of being in uncertainties ... without any irritable reaching after fact and reason".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has often been portrayed by Hollywood, almost always in a flattering light; the film historian Melvyn Stokes writes that "moviemakers have commonly used Lincoln primarily as a metaphor for ideas and values they approved".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's portrait appears on two denominations of United States currency, the penny and the $5 bill.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] He appears on postage stamps across the world, including in Ghana, Honduras, China, Haiti, Nicaragua, Colombia, and Argentina.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] He has been memorialized in many town, city, and county names, including the capital of Nebraska.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] The United States Navy has named three vessels after Lincoln, including the *Nimitz*-class aircraft carrier USS *Abraham Lincoln* (CVN-72).
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Lincoln Memorial in Washington, D.C., is one of the most visited National Park Service sites in the country.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] Memorials in Springfield, Illinois, include the Abraham Lincoln Presidential Library and Museum, Lincoln's home, and his tomb.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] A carving of Lincoln appears with those of three other presidents on Mount Rushmore, which receives about 3 million visitors a year.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] A statue of Lincoln completed by Augustus Saint-Gaudens stands in Lincoln Park, Chicago, with recastings given as diplomatic gifts standing in Parliament Square, London, and Parque Lincoln, Mexico City.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] Several states commemorate "Presidents' Day" as "Washington–Lincoln Day".
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has been extensively portrayed in media.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] Early works, such as *Abraham Lincoln's Clemency* (1910), attempted to mythologize him, emphasizing his mercifulness.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] Works from the Great Depression era, such as *Young Mr.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln* (1939), embellished his early struggles and folksiness.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] The 1938 play *Abe Lincoln in Illinois* won a Pulitzer Prize and was adapted in film.
[src:steamboat/abraham-lincoln-p03] After a marked decrease in film portrayals between 1941 and 1999, Daniel Day-Lewis won the Academy Award for Best Actor for his portrayal in *Lincoln*, a 2012 biographical film directed by Steven Spielberg.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The oldest city in New York, the City of Albany is the economic and cultural core of New York State's Capital District.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The Capital District is a metropolitan area including the nearby cities and suburbs of Colonie, Troy, Schenectady, and Saratoga Springs.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] With an estimated 1.3 million residents, the Capital District is one of the most populous metropolitan areas and is the fastest-growing region in Upstate New York.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The area that ultimately became Albany was originally inhabited by Algonquian-speaking Mohicans.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The area was settled by Dutch colonists, who built Fort Nassau in 1614 for fur trading and Fort Orange in 1624.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In 1664, the English took over the Dutch settlements, renaming the city "Albany" in honor of the Scottish title of the Duke of York (later James II of England and Ireland and James VII of Scotland): the Duke of Albany.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The city was officially chartered in 1686 under English rule.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] It became the capital of New York in 1797 after the formation of the United States.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is the oldest surviving settlement of the original British Thirteen Colonies north of Virginia.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In the late 18th century and throughout most of the 19th, Albany was a center of trade and transportation.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The city lies toward the north end of the navigable Hudson River.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] It was the original eastern terminus of the Erie Canal and was home to some of the earliest railroads in the world.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In the 1920s, a powerful political machine controlled by the Democratic Party emerged in Albany.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's population shrank because of urban sprawl and suburbanization in the latter part of the 20th century.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In the 1990s, the New York State Legislature approved for the city a US$234 million building and renovation plan, which spurred downtown redevelopment.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Since 2020, the economy of Albany and the surrounding Capital District has been directed toward artificial intelligence, AI-based photonics, quantum computing hardware manufacturing, nanotechnology, and digital electronics.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The Hudson River area was originally inhabited by Algonquian-speaking Mohicans, who called it *Pempotowwuthut-Muhhcanneuw*, meaning "the fireplace of the Mohican nation".
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Based to the west along the Mohawk River, the Iroquoian-speaking Mohawk called it *skahnéhtati*, also transliterated to Sche-negh-ta-da, "through the pine woods", referring to the path they took there.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] According to Hendrick Aupaumut, the Mohicans came to the area from the north and the west.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] They settled along the Mahicannituck River, which is now called the Hudson River, and called themselves the *Muh-he-con-neok*, the "People of the Waters That Are Never Still".
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The Mohawks, one of the Five Nations of the Iroquois Confederacy, were based in the Mohawk valley and noted for their fur trading and their access to trade between the Iroquois and other nations.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The Mohawk became strong trading partners with the Dutch and English.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] It is likely that the area was visited by European fur traders perhaps as early as 1540, but the extent and duration of those visits are unclear.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Permanent European claims began when Englishman Henry Hudson, exploring for the Dutch East India Company on the *Half Moon* (Dutch: *Halve Maen*), reached the area in 1609, claiming it for the United Netherlands.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In 1614, Hendrick Christiaensen built Fort Nassau on Castle Island (now called Port of Albany), in the Hudson River.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The fort acted as a fur-trading post and was the first documented European structure in present-day Albany.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Commencement of the fur trade provoked hostility from the French colony in Canada and among the natives, all of whom vied to control the trade.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In 1618, a flood ruined Fort Nassau, but the Dutch replaced it with Fort Orange on the mainland in 1624.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Both forts were named in honor of the leading family of the Dutch Revolt, members of the House of Orange-Nassau.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Fort Orange and the surrounding area were incorporated as the village of Beverwijck (English: Beaverwick or Beaver District) in 1652, and the city of Albany in 1686.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In these early decades of trade, the Dutch, Mohican, and Mohawk developed relations that reflected differences among their three cultures.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is one of the oldest surviving European settlements from the original Thirteen Colonies and the longest continuously chartered city in the United States.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] When New Netherland was captured by the English in 1664, the name was changed from *Beverwijck* to *Albany* in honor of Prince James, Duke of Albany (later King James VII/II).
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Duke of Albany was a Scottish title given since 1398, generally to a younger son of the King of Scots.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The name is ultimately derived from *Alba*, the Gaelic name for Scotland.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The Dutch briefly regained Albany in August 1673 and renamed the city *Willemstadt*; the English took permanent possession in 1674 with the Treaty of Westminster.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany was formally chartered as a municipality by provincial Governor Thomas Dongan on July 22, 1686.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The Dongan Charter was virtually identical in content to the charter awarded to the city of New York three months earlier.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Dongan created Albany as a strip of land 1 mile (1.6 km) wide and 16 miles (26 km) long.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Over the years Albany would lose much of the land to the west and annex land to the north and south.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] At this point, Albany had a population of about 500 people.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In 1754, representatives of seven British North American colonies met in the *Stadt Huys*, Albany's city hall, for the Albany Congress; Benjamin Franklin of Pennsylvania presented the Albany Plan of Union there, which was the first formal proposal to unite the colonies.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Although it was never adopted by Parliament, it was an important precursor to the United States Constitution.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The same year, the French and Indian War, the fourth in a series of wars dating back to 1689, began.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] It ended in 1763 with French defeat, resolving a situation that had been a constant threat to Albany and held back its growth.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Tories and prisoners of war were often jailed in the *Stadt Huys* alongside common criminals.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In 1776, Albany native Philip Livingston signed the Declaration of Independence.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] During and after the Revolutionary War, Albany County saw a great increase in real estate transactions.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] After the 1777 colonial victory at the Battle of Saratoga, the upper Hudson Valley was generally at peace as the war raged on elsewhere.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Prosperity was soon seen all over Upstate New York.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Migrants from Vermont and Connecticut began flowing in, noting the advantages of living on the Hudson and trading at Albany, while being only a few days' sail from New York City.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany reported a population of 3,498 in the first national census in 1790, an increase of almost 700% since its chartering.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] On November 17, 1793, fire broke out at a stable belonging to Leonard Gansevoort, destroying 26 homes on Broadway, Maiden Lane, James Street, and State Street.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Three were arrested and charged with arson: Pompey, a man belonging to Matthew Visscher; Dinah, a 14-year-old girl belonging to Volkert P.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Douw; and Bet, a 12-year-old girl belonging to Philip S.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] On January 6, 1794, the three were sentenced to death.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Governor George Clinton issued a temporary stay of execution, but Dinah and Bet were executed by hanging on March 14, and Pompey on April 11, 1794.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In 1797, the state capital was moved permanently to Albany.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] From statehood to this date, the Legislature had frequently moved the state capital between Albany, Kingston, Poughkeepsie, and the city of New York.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is the tenth-oldest state capital in the United States and the second-oldest city that is a state capital, after Santa Fe, New Mexico.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany has been a center of transportation for much of its history.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In the late 18th and early 19th centuries, Albany saw development of the turnpike and by 1815, Albany was the turnpike center of the state.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The development of Simeon De Witt's gridded block system in 1794—which renamed streets that had originally named after the British royal family with names of birds and mammals instead—was intersected by these major arterials coming out of Albany, cutting through the city at unexpected angles.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The construction of the turnpike, in conjunction with canal and railroad systems, made Albany the hub of transportation for pioneers going to Buffalo and the Michigan Territory in the early and mid-19th century.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In 1807, Robert Fulton initiated a steamboat line from New York City to Albany, the first successful enterprise of its kind anywhere in the world.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] By 1810, with 10,763 people, Albany was the tenth-largest urban place in the nation.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The town and village north of Albany known as "the Colonie" was annexed in 1815.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In 1825 the Erie Canal was completed, forming a continuous water route from the Great Lakes to New York City.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Unlike the current Barge Canal, which ends at nearby Waterford, the original Erie Canal ended at Albany; Lock 1 was north of Colonie Street.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The Canal emptied into a 32-acre (13 ha) man-made lagoon called the Albany Basin, which was Albany's main port from 1825 until the Port of Albany-Rensselaer opened in 1932.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In 1829, while working as a professor at the Albany Academy, Joseph Henry, widely regarded as "the foremost American scientist of the 19th century", built the first electric motor.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Three years later, he discovered electromagnetic self-induction (the SI unit for which is now the henry).
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] He went on to be the first Secretary of the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In the 1830 and 1840 censuses, Albany was ranked as the ninth-largest urban place in the nation; it dropped back to tenth in 1850.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] This was the last time the city was one of the top ten largest urban places in the nation.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany also has significant history with rail transport, as the location of two major regional railroad headquarters.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The Delaware and Hudson Railway was headquartered in Albany at what is now the SUNY System Administration Building.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In 1853, Erastus Corning, a noted industrialist and Albany's mayor from 1834 to 1837, consolidated ten railroads stretching from Albany to Buffalo into the New York Central Railroad (NYCRR), headquartered in Albany until Cornelius Vanderbilt moved it to New York City in 1867.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] One of the ten companies that formed the NYCRR was the Mohawk and Hudson Railroad, which was the first railroad in the state and the first successful steam railroad running regularly scheduled service in the country.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] While the key to Albany's economic prosperity in the 19th century was transportation, industry and business also played a role.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Largely thanks to the city's Dutch and German roots, beer was one of its biggest commodities.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Beverwyck Brewery, originally known as Quinn and Nolan (Nolan being mayor of Albany 1878–1883), was the last remaining brewer from that time when it closed in 1972.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The city's location at the east end of the Erie Canal gave it unparalleled access to both raw products and a captive customer base in the west.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany was known for its publishing houses, and to some extent, still is.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany was second only to Boston in the number of books produced for most of the 19th century.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Iron foundries in both the north and south ends of the city attracted thousands of immigrants to the city for industrial jobs.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Intricate wrought-iron details constructed in those years remain visible on what are now historic buildings.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The iron industry waned by the 1890s due to increased costs associated with a newly unionized workforce and the opening of mines in the Mesabi Range in Minnesota.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's other major exports during the 18th and 19th centuries were furs, wheat, meat, and lumber.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] By 1865, there were almost 4,000 saw mills in the Albany area and the Albany Lumber District was the largest lumber market in the nation.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The city was also home to a number of banks.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The Bank of Albany (1792–1861) was the second chartered bank in New York.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The city was the original home of the Albank (founded in 1820 as the Albany Savings Bank), KeyBank (founded in 1825 as the Commercial Bank of Albany), and Norstar Bank (founded as the State Bank of Albany in 1803).
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] American Express was founded in Albany in 1850 as an express mail business.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In 1871, the northwestern portion of Albany—west from Magazine Street—was annexed to the neighboring town of Guilderland after the town of Watervliet refused annexation of the territory.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In return for this loss, portions of Bethlehem and Watervliet were added to Albany.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Part of the land annexed to Guilderland was ceded back to Albany in 1910, setting up the current western border.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The train carrying the body of slain President Abraham Lincoln came through Albany on the way to Illinois and the ghostly image of that train remains.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany opened one of the first commercial airports in the world, and the first municipal airport in the United States, in 1908.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Originally on a polo field on Loudon Road, it moved to Westerlo Island in 1909 and remained there until 1928.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The Albany Municipal Airport—jointly owned by the city and county—was moved to its current location in Colonie in 1928.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] By 1916 Albany's northern and southern borders reached their modern courses; Westerlo Island, to the south, became the second-to-last annexation, which occurred in 1926.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Erastus Corning 2nd, arguably Albany's most notable mayor (and great-grandson of the former mayor of the same name), was elected in 1941.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] While Corning brought stability to the office of mayor, it is said even those who admire him greatly cannot come up with a sizable list of "major concrete Corning achievements." Corning is given credit for saving—albeit somewhat unintentionally—much of Albany's historic architecture.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] During the 1950s and 1960s, a time when federal aid for urban renewal was plentiful, Albany did not have growth in its economy or infrastructure.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] It lost more than 20 percent of its population during the Corning years, as people moved to newer housing in the suburbs, followed by most of the downtown businesses moving there as well.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] While cities across the country grappled with similar issues, the problems were magnified in Albany: interference from the Democratic political machine hindered progress considerably.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In 1960, the mayor sold the city's stake in the airport to the county, citing budget issues.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] It was known from then on as Albany County Airport until a massive upgrade and modernization project between 1996 and 1998, when it was rebranded Albany International Airport.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Governor Nelson Rockefeller (1959–1973) (R) tried to stimulate the city with new monumental architecture and large, government-sponsored building projects; he drove construction of the Empire State Plaza, SUNY Albany's uptown campus, and much of the W.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Averell Harriman State Office Building Campus.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany County Republican Chairman Joseph C.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Frangella once quipped, "Governor Rockefeller was the best mayor Albany ever had." Corning, although opposed to the project, was responsible for negotiating the payment plan for the Empire State Plaza.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Rockefeller did not want to be limited by the Legislature's power of the purse, so Corning devised a plan to have the county pay for the construction and have the state sign a lease-ownership agreement.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The state paid off the bonds until 2004.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] It was Rockefeller's only viable option, and he agreed.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Due to the clout Corning gained from the situation, he gained inclusion of the State Museum, a convention center, and a restaurant, back in the plans—ideas which Rockefeller had originally vetoed.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The county gained $35 million in fees and the city received $13 million for lost tax revenue.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Having the state offices in the city enabled it to keep good jobs and retain middle-class residents.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Another major project of the 1960s and 1970s was the construction of Interstate 787 and the South Mall Arterial.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] A proposed Mid-Crosstown Arterial never came to fruition.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] One of the project's main results was separating the city from the Hudson River.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] When Corning died in 1983, Thomas Whalen assumed the mayorship and was reelected twice.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] He encouraged redevelopment of historic structures and helped attract federal dollars earmarked for that purpose.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] What Corning had saved from destruction, Whalen refurbished for continued and new uses.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The Mayor's Office of Special Events was created in an effort to increase the number of festivals and artistic events in the city, including a year-long *Dongan Charter* tricentennial celebration in 1986.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Whalen is credited for an "unparalleled cycle of commercial investment and development" in Albany due to his "aggressive business development programs".
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Prior to the recession of the 1990s, downtown Albany was home to four Fortune 500 companies.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] After the death of Corning and the retirement of Congressman Sam Stratton, the political environment changed.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Long-term office holders became rare in the 1980s.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Local media began following the drama surrounding county politics (specifically that of the newly created county executive position); the loss of Corning (and eventually the machine) led to a lack of interest in city politics.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The election of Gerald Jennings was a surprise, and he served as mayor from 1994 until his retirement at the end of 2013.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] His tenure essentially ended the political machine that had been in place since the 1920s.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Many state workers were relocated from the Harriman State Office Campus to downtown, helping its retail businesses and vitality.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The first decade of the 21st century saw a real possibility for a long-discussed and controversial Albany Convention Center; it opened in 2017 with the goal of making Albany a viable location for large events hosted by statewide organizations.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany remains an important location for business presence, given its role as de facto seat of Tech Valley and being home to the state capitol.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Fortune 500 companies with offices in Albany include American Express, J.P.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Morgan and Chase, Merrill Lynch, General Electric, Verizon, Goldman Sachs, International Paper, and Key Bank.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany won the All-America City Award in both 1991 and 2009.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] is located at the extreme right of the image.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is about 135 miles (217 km) north of New York City on the Hudson River.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] It has a total area of 21.8 square miles (56 km2), of which 21.4 square miles (55 km2) is land and 0.4 square miles (1.0 km2) (1.8%) is water.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The city is bordered on the north by the town of Colonie (along with the village of Menands), on the west by the town of Guilderland, and on the south by the town of Bethlehem.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The former Foxes Creek, Beaver Kill, and Rutten Kill were diverted underground in the 19th century.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] There are four lakes within city limits: Buckingham Lake; Rensselaer Lake at the mouth of the Patroon Creek; Tivoli Lake, which was formed as a reservoir and once connected to the Patroon Creek; and Washington Park Lake, which was formed by damming the Beaver Kill.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The highest natural point in Albany is a USGS benchmark near the Loudonville Reservoir off Birch Hill Road, at 378 feet (115 m) above sea level.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The lowest point is at the Hudson River—which is still technically an estuary at Albany and is affected by the Atlantic tide—at an average of 2 feet (0.61 m) above sea level at low tide and 4 feet (1.2 m) at high tide.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The interior of Albany consists of rolling hills which were once part of the Albany Pine Bush, an area of pitch pine and scrub oak, and has arid, sandy soil that is a remnant of the ancient Lake Albany.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Due to development, the Pine Bush has shrunk from an original 25,000 to 6,000 acres (10,100 to 2,400 ha) today.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] A preserve was set up by the State Legislature in 1988 and is on the city's western edge, spilling into Guilderland and Colonie; it is the only sizable inland pine barrens sand dune ecosystem in the United States, and is home to many endangered species, including the Karner Blue butterfly.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is in the humid continental climate zone (Köppen climate classification: Dfa), and features cold, snowy winters, and hot, humid summers; the city experiences four distinct seasons.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is in plant hardiness zone 6a near downtown and along the shore of the Hudson and 5b at its western end.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany receives 40.7 inches (1,030 mm) of precipitation per year, with 138 days of at least 0.01 in (0.25 mm) of precipitation each year.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Snowfall is significant, totaling 59.4 inches (151 cm) per season, but with less accumulation than the lake effect areas to the north and west, as it is farther from Lake Ontario.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] However, Albany is close enough to the Atlantic coast to receive heavy snow from Nor'easters and the city occasionally receives Alberta clippers.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Winters can be very cold with fluctuating conditions; temperatures drop to 0 °F (−18 °C) or below on nine nights per annum.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Summers in Albany can contain stretches of excessive heat and humidity, with temperatures of 90 °F (32 °C) or hotter on nine days per year.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Due to the variety of its communities, Albany is often called a "city of neighborhoods." The neighborhoods of Albany include Arbor Hill; Center Square, "[an] eclectic mix of residential and commercial [buildings], including bars, night clubs, restaurants, and stores"; Pine Hills; and the South End.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Historically, Albany's population has been mixed.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] First dominated by Mohican and Mohawk people, then Dutch and Germans, it was overtaken by the British in the early 19th century.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Irish immigrants soon outnumbered most other ethnicities by the mid-19th century, and were followed by Italians and Poles.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In the mid-to-late 20th century, the African-American population increased with thousands of people from the rural South, as part of the Great Migration.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Until after the Revolution, Albany's population consisted mostly of ethnic Dutch descendants.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Settlers migrating from New England tipped the balance toward British ethnicity in the early 19th century.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Jobs on the turnpikes, canals, and railroads attracted floods of Irish immigrants in the early 19th century, especially in the 1840s during the Great Famine, solidifying the city's Irish base.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Michael Nolan became Albany's first Irish Catholic mayor in 1878, two years before Boston.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Polish and Italian immigrants began arriving in Albany in the wave of immigration in the latter part of the 19th century.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Their numbers were smaller than in many other eastern cities mainly because most had found manufacturing jobs at General Electric in Schenectady.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The Jewish community had been established early, with Sephardic Jewish members as part of the Beverwijck community.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Its population rose during the late 19th century, when many Ashkenazi Jews immigrated from eastern Europe.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In that period, there was also an influx of Chinese and east Asian immigrants, who settled in the downtown section of the city.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Many of their descendants have since moved to suburban areas.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Asian immigration all but halted after the Immigration Act of 1924.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany saw its last large immigration pattern as part of the Great Migration when many African Americans moved there from the American South before and after World War I to fill industrial positions and find other opportunities.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In the early years, African-Americans lived together with Italians, Jews, and other immigrants in the South End, where housing was older and less expensive.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The black community has grown as a proportion of the population since then; African Americans made up three percent of the city's population in 1950, six percent in 1960, 12 percent in 1970, and 30 percent in 2010.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The change in proportion is related mostly to middle-class white families moving to the suburbs and black families remaining within city limits during the same time period.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Since 2007, the number of Burmese refugees to Albany has increased.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The Burmese refugee community consists mostly of people of Karen ethnicity.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] An estimated 5,000 Burmese refugees reside in Albany as of January 2015.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Like most cities of comparable age and size, Albany has well-established Orthodox Christian, Roman Catholic, Protestant, and Jewish communities.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is home to the oldest Christian congregation in Upstate New York and the Mother Churches of two Christian dioceses.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] As of June 2010, eight churches or religious buildings in the city were listed on the National Register of Historic Places, one of which—St.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Peter's Episcopal Church on State Street—is a National Historic Landmark.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Established in 1642, the congregation of the First Church in Albany (Reformed), also known as the North Dutch Church (on North Pearl Street), is the second-oldest Reformed Church in America.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] As of 2023, the city was home to twelve Catholic churches and four Episcopal churches.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Despite its history of Christendom, in 2019 the Albany-Schenectady-Troy MSA was found to be among the most post-Christian cities in the United States in a study by Christian polling firm The Barna Group.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] A significant Jewish presence has existed in Albany as early as 1658.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] As of 2010, Albany is home to two Conservative synagogues, a Chabad-Lubavitch synagogue, an Orthodox synagogue, and two Reform synagogues.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is also home to one of the few Karaite synagogues outside Israel.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] As of 2008, the total membership in Albany's synagogues was estimated at 12,000–13,000, with half the members residing outside the city.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Since the early 2000s, there has been an increase in Orthodox Jews moving to Albany from the New York Metro area, largely due to cheaper housing prices and closer walking proximity to synagogues.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The Islamic community in Albany and its surrounding suburbs is represented by at least four major mosques in the region.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The Muslim population increased substantially starting in the late 2000s, with the arrival of many refugees from countries such as Iraq, Syria, and Afghanistan.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Exact numbers on religious denominations in Albany are not readily available.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Demographic statistics in the United States depend heavily on the United States Census Bureau, which cannot ask about religious affiliation as part of its decennial census.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] It does compile some national and statewide religious statistics, but these are not representative of a city the size of Albany.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] One report from 2000 offers religious affiliations for Albany County.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] According to the data, 59.2% of Albany County residents identified as Christian: 47% are Roman Catholic, 8.4% are mainline Protestants, 2.7% are Evangelical Protestants, and 1.1% are Eastern or Oriental Orthodox Christians.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Residents who practice Judaism make up 4.2% of the population and Muslims represent 0.2%.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] As of the 2020 census, Albany had a population of 99,224.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] 17.8% of residents were under the age of 18 and 13.3% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] For every 100 females there were 93.5 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 91.3 males age 18 and over.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] 100.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] There were 42,158 households in Albany, of which 21.8% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Of all households, 22.4% were married-couple households, 29.1% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 39.5% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] About 43.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] There were 48,031 housing units, of which 12.2% were vacant.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The homeowner vacancy rate was 2.7% and the rental vacancy rate was 7.8%.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] According to the 2020 American Community Survey, the Latino population was: 4.57% Puerto Rican, 1.45% Dominican, .84% Ecuadorian, .77% Mexican, .69% Salvadoran, .22% Cuban.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] As of the 2010 census, Albany's population density was 4,572.7 inhabitants per square mile (1,765.5/km2).
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] There were 46,362 housing units at an average density of 2,166.4 per square mile (836.5/km2); 5,205 of these units (11.2%) were vacant.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The racial makeup of the city residents was 52.3% white; 27% Black or African American; 0.06% Native American or Native Alaskan; 7.4% Asian; 0.1% Native Hawaiian or Pacific Islander; .06% from other races; and 3.6% from two or more races.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] A total of 9.2% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Non-Hispanic Whites were 52.0% of the population in 2010, compared to 87.0% in 1970.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] For every 100 females, there were 90.6 males.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 86.5 males.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Some 81.3% of the population had completed high school or earned an equivalency diploma.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] As of the 2000 census, the top five ancestry groups in the city were African American (27%), Irish (18.1%), Italian (12.4%), German (10.4%), and English (5.2%); (33.1%) of the population reported "other ancestries".
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is home to a Triqui language-speaking community of Mexican-Americans.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] There were 40,709 households in Albany in 2000, of which 22.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 25.3% were married couples living together, 16.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 54.8% were non-families.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] 41.9% of all households were made up of individuals, and 11.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The average household size was 2.11 and the average family size was 2.95.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The median income for a household in the city in 2000 was $96,713, and the median income for a family was $100,374 (male, year-round worker) and $91,052 (female, year-round worker).
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The per capita income for the city was $73,985.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] About 16.0% of families and 21.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including 28.8% of those under age 18 and 12.5% of those age 65 or over.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The rate of reported violent crimes for 2008 (1,095 incidents per 100,000 residents) were more than double the rate for similarly sized US cities.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Reported property crimes (4,669 incidents per 100,000 residents) were somewhat lower.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] With a 2013 Census-estimated population of 1.1 million, the eight county Capital District, encompassing Albany, Troy, Schenectady and Saratoga, is the third-most populous metropolitan region in the state.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Demographically speaking, the population of Albany and the Capital District mirrors the characteristics of the United States consumer population as a whole better than any other major municipality in the country.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] According to a 2004 study conducted by the Acxiom Corporation, Albany and its environs are the top-ranked standard test market for new business and retail products.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany, Rochester, and Syracuse all scored within the top five.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's violent crime rate was 10.03 per 1,000 residents in 2023, compared to 7.69 in Buffalo, 7.39 in Rochester, 8.22 in Syracuse, and 7.72 in New York City.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] New York State had statewide violent crime rate of 3.90 per 1,000 people in 2023.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's economy, along with that of the Capital District in general, is heavily dependent on government, health care, education, and more recently, technology.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Because of these typically steady economic bases, the local economy has been relatively immune to national economic recessions in the past.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In 2009, more than 25 percent of the city's population worked in government-related positions.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's estimated daytime population is more than 162,000.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Companies based in Albany include Trans World Entertainment, AMRI Global and Clough Harbour.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] In 2019, Albany had the fourth-highest amount of lawyers in its employment pool (7.5 lawyers per 1,000 jobs) compared to the rest of the nation, behind Washington, D.C., Trenton, New Jersey, and New York City, respectively.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Since the 2000s, the economy of Albany and the surrounding Capital District has been directed toward high technology, a growing fourth sector of the area's economic base.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] Tech Valley is a marketing name for the eastern part of New York State, encompassing Albany, the Capital District, and the Hudson Valley.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] The area's high technology ecosystem is supported by technologically focused academic institutions including Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute and the State University of New York Polytechnic Institute.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p01] A notable video game development cluster has grown in and around Albany starting in the 2010s.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's geographic situation—roughly equidistant from New York City to the south and Montreal to the north—makes it a convenient stop for nationally touring artists and acts.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Palace Theatre and The Egg are mid-sized forums for music, theater, and spoken-word performances; the Capital Repertory Theatre is smaller.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The MVP Arena is the city's largest musical venue for nationally and internationally prominent bands.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] It also hosts trade shows, sporting events, and other large gatherings.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] In recent years, the city's government has invested resources to cultivate venues and neighborhoods that attract after-hours business.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Madison Avenue, Pearl Street, Delaware Avenue and Lark Street are the most active entertainment areas in the city.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Many restaurants, clubs, and bars have opened since the mid-1990s, revitalizing areas that had once been abandoned and reclaiming old row houses, businesses, and a pump station.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Much of the bar restaurant scene features classic Irish Pubs.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Price Chopper Fabulous Fourth and Fireworks Festival at the Empire State Plaza celebrates Independence Day with musical performances and the region's largest fireworks display.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Chefs' Food & Wine Festival donates all net proceeds to deserving Albany Arts Organizations and is held the Thursday-Saturday preceding Martin Luther King Weekend.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Because of Albany's historical and political significance, the city has numerous museums, historical buildings, and historic districts.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is home to the New York State Museum, the New York State Library and the New York State Archives; all three facilities are in the Cultural Education Center at the south end of Empire State Plaza and are free to the public.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The USS *Slater* (DE-766), a decommissioned World War II destroyer escort that was restored in 1998, is a museum ship docked in the Hudson River at Quay Street.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] It is the only ship of its kind still afloat.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Heritage Area Visitors Center, at the corner of Clinton Avenue and Broadway at Quackenbush Square, hosts a museum, gift shop, and the Henry Hudson Planetarium.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] In early 2012, the Irish American Heritage Museum opened in downtown Albany.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The museum is home to exhibits highlighting the contributions of the Irish people in America.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is home to 57 listings on the National Register of Historic Places (NRHP) and five National Historic Landmarks.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Ten Broeck Mansion, a 1797 Federal-style mansion (later renovated in the Greek-Revival style) built for Abraham Ten Broeck (mayor of Albany 1779–1783 and 1796–1798) is a historic house museum and the headquarters of the Albany County Historical Association; it was added to the NRHP in 1971.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Later known as "Arbor Hill", it gave the current neighborhood its name.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has been the subject, inspiration, or location for many written and cinematic works.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Many non-fiction works have been written on the city.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] One of the city's more notable claims to fame is *Ironweed* (1983), the 1984 Pulitzer Prize-winning book by Albany native William Kennedy.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] *Ironweed* was the third in a series of books by Kennedy known as the "Albany Cycle".
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The elusive author Trevanian also grew up in Albany and wrote *The Crazyladies of Pearl Street* (2005), about a North Albany neighborhood along Pearl Street.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The book is considered a semi-autobiographical memoir.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] In 1987, the film version of *Ironweed* premiered at the Palace Theatre.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The movie starred Jack Nicholson and Meryl Streep, each of whom were nominated for Academy Awards for their performances; much of the filming was done on location in Albany.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Most recently the downtown area was the site of filming for the action-thriller *Salt*, starring Angelina Jolie, and the action-comedy *The Other Guys*, starring Will Ferrell and Mark Wahlberg.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Authors Herman Melville and Henry James lived with their families in Albany when young, before their careers.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] James identified his character Isabel Archer, the heroine of his novel *The Portrait of a Lady*, as being from Albany.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Gregory Maguire, author of *Wicked: The Life and Times of the Wicked Witch of the West* (adapted for the Broadway hit *Wicked*), grew up in North Albany and graduated from SUNY Albany.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Empire State Plaza, a collection of state agency office buildings, dominates almost any view of Albany.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Built between 1965 and 1978 at the hand of Governor Nelson A.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Rockefeller and architect Wallace Harrison, the complex is a powerful example of late American modern architecture and remains a controversial building project both for displacing city residents and for its architectural style.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The most recognizable aspect of the complex is the Erastus Corning Tower, the tallest building in New York outside of New York City.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Juxtaposed at the north end of the Plaza is the 19th-century New York State Capitol, the seat of the New York State Legislature and the home of the Governor's office.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's initial architecture incorporated many Dutch influences, followed soon after by those of the English.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Quackenbush House, a Dutch Colonial brick mansion, was built c.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] 1736; Schuyler Mansion, a Georgian-style mansion, was built in 1765; and the oldest building in Albany is the 1728 Van Ostrande-Radliff House at 48 Hudson Avenue.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's housing varies greatly, with mostly row houses in the older sections of town, closer to the river.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Housing type quickly changes as one travels westward, beginning with two-family homes of the late 19th century, and one-family homes built after World War II in the western end of the city.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany City Hall, designed by Henry Hobson Richardson, was opened in 1883.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Capitol was opened in 1899 (after 32 years of construction) at a cost of $25 million, making it the most expensive government building at the time.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's Union Station, a major Beaux-Arts design, was under construction at the same time; it opened in 1900.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] In 1912, the Beaux-Arts styled New York State Department of Education Building opened on Washington Avenue near the Capitol.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] It has a classical exterior, which features a block-long white marble colonnade.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The 1920s brought the Art Deco movement, which is illustrated by the Home Savings Bank Building (1927) on North Pearl Street and the Alfred E.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Smith Building (1930) on South Swan Street, two of Albany's tallest high-rises.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Architecture from the 1960s and 1970s is well represented in the city, especially at the W.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Averell Harriman State Office Building Campus (1950s and 1960s) and on the uptown campus of the University at Albany (1962–1971).
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The state office campus was planned in the 1950s by governor W.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Averell Harriman to offer more parking and easier access for state employees.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The uptown SUNY campus was built in the 1960s under Governor Rockefeller on the site of the city-owned Albany Country Club.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Straying from the popular open campus layout, SUNY Albany has a centralized building layout with administrative and classroom buildings at center surrounded by four student housing towers.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The design called for much use of concrete and glass, and the style has slender, round-topped columns and pillars reminiscent of those at Lincoln Center in New York City.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Downtown has seen a revival in recent decades, often considered to have begun with Norstar Bank's renovation of the former Union Station as its corporate headquarters in 1986.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Knickerbocker Arena (MVP Arena) was originally slated for suburban Colonie, but was instead built downtown and opened in 1990.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has teams in two top-level professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada (New York Atlas, and Albany Firebirds), and several minor-league sports teams with varying levels of support.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Devils were a minor league ice hockey team that moved to the city for the 2010–11 season.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] They played in the American Hockey League and were affiliated with the New Jersey Devils of the National Hockey League.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Devils replaced the Albany River Rats, who played in the Capital Region from 1990 to 2010, when they relocated to Charlotte, North Carolina.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Devils moved to Binghamton, New York in 2017.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Times Union Center has previously hosted arena football teams including the Albany Firebirds in the Arena Football League (AFL) from 1990 to 2000 and then a team originally known as the Albany Conquest and later the Firebirds in the af2, the AFL's developmental league, from 2002 to 2009.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Empire played in the AFL from 2018 through the 2019 season when the league folded.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] A new Albany Empire was relaunched in the National Arena League for the 2021 season.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] In 2023, Antonio Brown bought the team; after a series of problems with payments and personnel, the NAL suspended the franchise in the middle of the 2023 season.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] A relaunched Albany Firebirds franchise began playing in 2024.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Tri-City ValleyCats short season minor league baseball team have played at the Joseph L.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Bruno Stadium on the Hudson Valley Community College campus in North Greenbush since 2002.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Prior to the ValleyCats' arrival, the Albany-Colonie Diamond Dogs (1995–2002) played at Heritage Park in Colonie; due to financial pressures, and facing impending competition from the ValleyCats, the franchise folded in 2002.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Legends (International Basketball League), played in the Washington Avenue Armory from 2010 to 2014 before moving to Schenectady.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Patroons have played at the Armory on and off since 1982 and currently play in The Basketball League.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] With the large number of local colleges and universities around Albany, college sports are popular.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The University at Albany's Great Danes play at the Division I level in all sports.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The football team is a member of the Coastal Athletic Association while all other sports teams play as members of the America East Conference.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] In 2006, UAlbany became the first SUNY-affiliated school to send a team to the NCAA Division I men's basketball tournament.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Siena Saints saw a rise in popularity after their men's basketball team made it to the NCAA Tournament in 2008, 2009, and 2010.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] All 18 Saints teams are Division I and play in the Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Although Siena's campus is in nearby Colonie, the men's basketball team plays at the Times Union Center.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] UAlbany hosted the New York Giants training camp from 1996 to 2012.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] On February 23, 2021, it was announced that the National Lacrosse League (NLL) would return to the city with the relocation of the New England Black Wolves.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The team was named the Albany FireWolves on April 15, 2021.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] This is the second NLL team to be based in the area; the first, the Albany Attack, played in the city from 2000 to 2003.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] In 2023, the Premier Lacrosse League (PLL) selected cities for their 8 franchises, and Albany was chosen as the primary home for the New York Atlas.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] In 2024, the Albany Firebirds began playing in the AFL at the MVP Arena.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] After one season in the AFL, the team moved to the AF1.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The 518 Ballers (American Basketball Association) have played at Our Savior's Christian School since 2023.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has more than 60 public parks and recreation areas.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Washington Park was organized as the Middle Public Square in 1806.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Its current location has been public property since the *Dongan Charter* of 1686 gave the city title to all property not privately owned.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Washington Park was designed by John Bogart and John Cuyler in 1870, and opened for public use the following year.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The original lake house, designed by Frederick W.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The park had previously been used as a cemetery; its graves were moved to Albany Rural Cemetery.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Washington Park is a popular place to exercise and play sports; skate during the winter; people-watch during Tulip Fest; and attend plays at the amphitheater during the summer.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Other parks in Albany include Lincoln Park, Buckingham Park, the Corning Preserve, the Albany Skyway and the Pine Bush.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Lincoln Park, southwest of the Empire State Plaza, was organized in 1886 and was originally known as Beaver Park.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Today, the park has a pool that is open during the summer months.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Buckingham Lake Park is between Manning Boulevard and Route 85 in the Buckingham Pond neighborhood; it contains a pond with fountains, a footpath, a playground, and picnic tables.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Riverfront Park at the Corning Preserve has an 800-seat amphitheatre that hosts events in non-winter months, most notably the *Alive at 5* summer concert series.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Preserve's visitors center details the ecology of the Hudson River and the local environment.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The park has a bike trail and boat launch and was effectively separated from downtown by Interstate 787 until the opening of the Hudson River Way in 2002.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Other public parks include Westland Hill Park, Hoffman Park, Beverwyck Park, and Liberty Park, today a small circular grassy patch in downtown on Hudson Avenue, which is Albany's oldest park.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Ridgefield Park is home to the clay courts of the Albany Tennis Club, one of the oldest tennis clubs in the United States.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The municipal golf course, New Course at Albany, was constructed in 1929 as the Albany Municipal Golf Course, later renamed the Capital Hills at Albany, and remodeled in 1991.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has a strong mayor-council government, which functions under the Dongan Charter, granted by colonial governor Thomas Dongan in 1686 when Albany was incorporated.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] A revised charter was adopted by referendum in 1998, but was legally reckoned as an amendment to the Dongan Charter.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] This gives Albany the distinction of having the oldest active city charter in the United States and "arguably the longest-running instrument of municipal government in the Western Hemisphere." The mayor, who is elected every four years, heads the executive branch of city government.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The current mayor, Kathy Sheehan, was first elected in 2013.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Common Council represents the legislative branch of city government and is made up of fifteen council members (each elected from one ward) and an at-large Common Council President.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The current president is Corey Ellis; he began his term in January 2018.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] While Albany has its own city government, it has also been the seat of Albany County since the county's formation in 1683 and the capital of New York since 1797.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] As such, the city is home to all branches of the county and state governments, as well as its own.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany City Hall sits on Eagle Street, opposite the State Capitol, and the Albany County Office Building is on State Street.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The state government has offices scattered throughout the city.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is in the 20th Congressional district, represented by Paul Tonko (D) in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The city is represented by Chuck Schumer (D) and Kirsten Gillibrand (D) in the United States Senate.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] On the state level, the city is in the 44th district in the New York Senate, represented by Patricia Fahy (D).
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] In the New York Assembly, western Albany is in the 109th district, represented by Gabriella Romero (D) while downtown and eastern Albany are in the 108th district, represented by John T.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] As the seat of Albany County, the city is the location of the county's courts including Family Court, County Court, Surrogate Court, Supreme Court, and New York Court of Appeals.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is the site of a federal courthouse that houses the United States District Court for the Northern District of New York.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's politics have been dominated by the Democratic Party since the 1920s; Daniel (Uncle Dan) O'Connell established a political machine in the city with the election of William Stormont Hackett as mayor in 1922.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Prior to that, William Barnes Jr. had set up a Republican machine in the 1890s.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Barnes' success is attributed to the fact that he owned two newspapers in Albany and that he was the grandson of Thurlow Weed, the influential newspaper publisher and political boss.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] O'Connell's organization overcame Barnes' in 1922 and survived well into the 1980s (even after his death).
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] In many instances, votes were outright bought.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Gerald Jennings' upset in the 1993 Democratic mayoral primary over Harold Joyce, who had the Democratic Party's formal endorsement and had only recently been its county chairman, is often cited as the end of the O'Connell era in Albany.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] In the early 21st century, Albany continued to be dominated by the Democratic Party.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] As a measure of the party's dominance, Democratic enrollment in the city was 38,862 in 2009, while Republican enrollment was 3,487.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] As of 2022, the mayor's office had been in Democratic hands since 1922, and every elected city position had been held by a Democrat since 1931.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] In November 2013, Kathy Sheehan became the first woman to be elected Mayor of Albany.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The City School District of Albany (CSDA) operates the city's public school system, which consists of 17 schools and learning centers; in addition, there are 7 charter schools, including Green Tech Charter High School, and Albany Leadership High School.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] In the 2015–2016 school year, over 9,000 students were enrolled in the public school system.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The district had an average class size of 18, an 81-percent graduation rate, and a 5-percent dropout rate.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Although considered by the state to be one of the lowest-achieving high schools in New York, Albany High was listed as the nation's 976th best high school in a 2010 *Newsweek/Washington Post* report.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany also has a number of private schools, including the coed Bishop Maginn High School and Albany Free School; the all-boys Albany Academy; and the all-girls Academy of the Holy Names and Albany Academy for Girls.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Medical College (private), today part of Albany Medical Center, was founded in 1839.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany Law School (private) is the oldest law school in New York and the fourth-oldest in the country; it was opened in 1851.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] President William McKinley was an alumnus.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany College of Pharmacy and Health Sciences (private) is the second-oldest pharmacy school in New York and the fifteenth-oldest in the United States.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Normal School, one of the oldest teachers colleges in the United States, opened in 1844; it was later known as the State Teachers College.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] It eventually evolved into the University at Albany, also known as SUNY Albany (public), which inherited the Normal School's original downtown campus on Western Avenue.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The center of the campus moved to its current Uptown Campus in the west end of the city in 1970.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] SUNY Albany is a unit of the State University of New York and one of only four university centers in the system.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Other colleges and universities in Albany include Empire State College, The College of Saint Rose, Excelsior College, Maria College, Mildred Elley, and Sage College of Albany.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Nearby Hudson Valley Community College (HVCC) fills the community college niche in the Albany-Troy area.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The effect of the campuses on the city's population is substantial: Combining the student bodies of all the aforementioned campuses (except HVCC) results in 63,149 students, or almost 70 percent of the 2008 estimate of Albany's permanent population.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The *Times Union* is Albany's primary daily newspaper and the only one based close to the city; its headquarters moved from within city limits to suburban Colonie in the 1960s after a dispute with Mayor Corning over land needed for expansion.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Its circulation totals about 73,000 on weekdays and 143,000 on Sundays.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Serving Albany to a lesser degree are *The Daily Gazette*, based in Schenectady, and *The Record*, of Troy.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] *Metroland* is the alternative newsweekly in the area, publishing each Thursday, while *The Business Review* is a business weekly published each Friday.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The *Legislative Gazette*, another weekly newspaper, focuses exclusively on issues related to the Legislature and the state government.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] As of 2010, the Albany-Schenectady-Troy media market is the 63rd-largest in the country in terms of radio and the 57th-largest in terms of television audiences.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] It is a broadcast market with historical significance.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The pioneering influence of General Electric in Schenectady directly contributed to the area emerging as the birthplace of station-based television with WRGB; the station was also the first affiliate of NBC.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] In 1947, the region was home to the first independently owned and operated commercial FM radio station in the United States: W47A.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] WGY was the second commercial radio station in New York and the twelfth in the nation.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Capital District is home to ABC affiliate WTEN 10, CBS affiliate WRGB 6 (also operating CW affiliate WCWN 45), Fox affiliate WXXA 23, NBC affiliate WNYT 13 (also operating MyNetworkTV affiliate WNYA 51), and PBS member station WMHT 17.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Charter Communications hosts Spectrum News Capital Region, the area's only local 24-hour news channel.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Thruway is the most prominent highway serving Albany.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] From Albany westward, it is part of Interstate 90, connecting Albany with major cities such as Syracuse, Rochester and Buffalo.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] To the south, it becomes part of Interstate 87 and leads to New York City.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] A short un-tolled section of Interstate 90 extends around the northern and eastern portions of Albany before linking back up with the Berkshire extension of the Thruway, which leads to the Massachusetts Turnpike and ultimately to Boston.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] North of Albany, Interstate 87 follows the Northway to Canada at Champlain; Autoroute 15 continues into Quebec, linking Albany to Montreal.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Interstate 787 links downtown Albany to the southbound I-87/Thruway to the south, while to the north, it links with the free portion of Interstate 90 before continuing to Troy, Watervliet, Colonie, and Menands.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] By way of Route 7, I-787 connects to the Northway.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Since the closure of Union Station on Broadway, area passenger-rail service is provided by Amtrak at the Albany-Rensselaer station across the river in Rensselaer.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] In 2009, the station saw more than 720,000 passengers, making it Amtrak's second-busiest in New York, behind Manhattan's Penn Station.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Amtrak provides service south to New York City; north to Montreal, and Burlington (Vermont); west to Niagara Falls, Toronto and Chicago; and east to Boston.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's major airport is Albany International Airport in Colonie.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Major airline service to Albany includes service by: American Airlines, Delta Air Lines, Southwest Airlines, JetBlue Airways, and United Airlines; Million Air is the local fixed-base operator.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] In 2010, Albany had the highest average airfare in New York, though the per-mile cost on its busiest routes was second-lowest in the state.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The Capital District Transportation Authority (CDTA) provides bus service throughout Albany and the surrounding area, including Schenectady, Troy, and Saratoga Springs.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The city was once served by an urban streetcar service maintained by the United Traction Company.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] As in many American cities, after the advent of the automobile, light rail services declined in Albany and were replaced by bus and taxi services.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Greyhound Lines, Trailways, Peter Pan, Short Line, Vermont Translines, and Yankee Trails buses all serve a downtown terminal.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Low-cost curbside bus service from the SUNY Albany campus and the Rensselaer station is also provided by Megabus, with direct service to New York City.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Albany, long an important Hudson River port, today serves domestic and international ships and barges through the Port of Albany-Rensselaer, on both sides of the river.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The port has the largest mobile harbor crane in the state of New York.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Barge Canal, the ultimate successor of the Erie Canal, is in use today, largely by tourist and private boats.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] The city of Nijmegen, Netherlands connected with Albany following World War II.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] With the help of the Catholic university in Albany, the Catholic University of Nijmegen (Radboud University Nijmegen) rebuilt its partly destroyed library, with over 50,000 books being donated to the Dutch university.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] To show its gratitude for post-war assistance, the city sent Albany 50,000 tulip bulbs in 1948; this act led to the establishment of the annual Tulip Festival.
[src:steamboat/albany-new-york-p02] Most of the other connections were made in the 1980s during Mayor Whalen's term in office as part of his cultural expansion program.
[src:steamboat/alexander-carnegie-kirk] Alexander Carnegie Kirk was the eldest son of Rev.
[src:steamboat/alexander-carnegie-kirk] John Kirk (died 1858) and Christian Guthrie, née Carnegie, (died 1865).
[src:steamboat/alexander-carnegie-kirk] The naturalist John Kirk was his younger brother.
[src:steamboat/alexander-carnegie-kirk] Kirk married Ada Waller at Croydon in 1869 and they had six children.
[src:steamboat/alexander-carnegie-kirk] In 1850, Kirk began a five-year apprenticeship with Robert Napier and Sons.
[src:steamboat/alexander-carnegie-kirk] In 1861, he became chief draughtsman at Maudslay, Sons and Field in London but this seems to have lasted less than a year.
[src:steamboat/alexander-carnegie-kirk] Later in 1861 he became an engineering manager in the shale-oil industry, working for James Young.
[src:steamboat/alexander-carnegie-kirk] During this employment he developed an oil shale retort and a refrigeration technology, involving the delivery of ether.
[src:steamboat/alexander-carnegie-kirk] The latter was to address production problems stemming from summer heat.
[src:steamboat/alexander-carnegie-kirk] In 1865 he joined the management of James Aitken and Company, an engine works in Glasgow.
[src:steamboat/alexander-carnegie-kirk] In 1870 he was appointed manager of the John C.
[src:steamboat/alexander-carnegie-kirk] After returning to the Napier firm as a senior partner in 1877, his work was thereafter focused on marine engineering.
[src:steamboat/alexander-carnegie-kirk] His triple-expansion engines as designed for the steamship *Propontis* were unsuccessful, but his subsequent versions of the engine design, particularly those designed for the steamship *Aberdeen*, are credited as technological breakthroughs.
[src:steamboat/alexander-carnegie-kirk] He served as the President of The Institution of Engineers and Shipbuilders in Scotland from 1887 to 1889.
[src:steamboat/alexander-carnegie-kirk] In 2020 he was inducted into the Scottish Engineering Hall of Fame.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The **Allaire Iron Works** was a leading 19th-century American marine engineering company based in New York City.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Founded in 1816 by engineer and philanthropist James P.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Allaire, the Allaire Works was one of the world's first companies dedicated to the construction of marine steam engines, supplying the engines for more than 50% of all the early steamships built in the United States.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Allaire retired from the company in 1850 when it was taken over by Cornelius Vanderbilt.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] During Vanderbilt's ownership, the Allaire Iron Works made a significant contribution to the Union cause during the American Civil War.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Following the war, the Allaire Works, like many other American marine engineering companies, fell on hard times, and in 1869 it was wound up, whereupon its equipment was purchased by John Roach, who also hired its best employees for his own company, the Morgan Iron Works.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Amongst the many notable achievements of the Allaire Works, it supplied the engine cylinder for the first steamship to cross the Atlantic, *Savannah*, pioneered the use of the compound engine in steamships, and built the engines for two winners of the coveted Blue Riband.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The company also supplied the engines for at least 17 U.S.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Navy warships during the American Civil War.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] James Peter Allaire founded his first company, a brass foundry, at 466 Cherry Street, New York, in 1804.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] In 1807, Allaire received an order from steamboat pioneer Robert Fulton for brass fittings for the *North River Steamboat*, the world's first commercially successful steam-powered vessel.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Allaire and Fulton struck up a friendship, and Allaire provided fittings for later vessels built by Fulton.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Following Fulton's death in 1815, Allaire leased his plant and equipment from the Fulton and Livingstone families, and entered a partnership with Fulton's chief engineer, Charles Stoudinger.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Allaire and Stoudinger built the engine and boiler for the last steamboat contracted for by the Fulton shop, the *Chancellor Livingstone*, which was completed about a year later.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Stoudinger himself died shortly after completion of *Chancellor Livingstone*, after which Allaire decided to move Fulton's equipment from its location in New Jersey to his brassworks at Cherry St., New York.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] With the consolidation of his business at the Cherry St. plant, Allaire renamed it the **Allaire Iron Works**.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] In 1817, the Allaire Iron Works supplied the engine cylinder for *Savannah*, the first steamship to make a transatlantic crossing.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The cylinder, one of the largest then built, had a diameter of 40 inches (1,000 mm), while the piston had a stroke of 5 feet.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] *Savannah* was not a commercial success, and following her return voyage from Europe, her engine was removed and sold to Allaire.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] In 1819, the Allaire Works supplied the engine for *Robert Fulton*, the first steamship to enter service along the United States coastline (as opposed to working the inland waterways).
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] This engine had a 44-inch-diameter (110 cm) cylinder and a stroke of 5 feet.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] *Robert Fulton* helped to demonstrate that steamships were capable of reliable seagoing service.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Other engines built in this period by the Allaire Works include those for *United States*—a 140-foot steamer said to be the first American steamboat to issue tickets (rather than "way-bills") to passengers—and for *James Kent*, *North Carolina*, *South Carolina* and other Hudson River steamers.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] As Allaire's business grew, he found it increasingly difficult to source adequate amounts of quality pig iron from which to manufacture his engines.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The best quality pig iron was imported from Britain, but high tariffs made it uneconomic to use.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The pig iron industry in the United States was at this time still in its infancy, and producing neither the quality nor quantity of pig iron required.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The only solution was for Allaire to become a manufacturer of pig iron himself.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] In 1822, in response to a recommendation from a friend, Allaire purchased 7,000 acres (28 km2) of land in Monmouth County, New Jersey, which contained a furnace used for manufacturing pig iron from the natural resource of bog iron.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Allaire renamed the furnace the Howell Works, and over the next 20 years used it to source most of his pig iron, during which time Howell Works grew to be a substantial and largely self-sufficient community, complete with its own church, school, company store and farmland.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] In 1824, the Allaire Works built the engine for the steamboat *Henry Eckford*, the first steam vessel in the world fitted with a compound engine.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The high-pressure cylinder was 12 inches (300 mm) in diameter and the low-pressure cylinder 24 inches (610 mm), with both having a stroke of 4 feet.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] In the same year, the Allaire Works also supplied a compound engine for a 200-ton towboat called *Post Boy*, and another for a small steamer, *Linnaeus*.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Other vessels equipped with compound engines from the Allaire Works to 1828 included *Sun*, *Commerce*, *Swiftsure* and *Pilot Boy*.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The Allaire Works built compound engines decades before the advantages of such engines became widely recognized in the shipbuilding industry.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] In the 1830s, the Allaire business empire reached the peak of its expansion.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The Howell Works in New Jersey was producing a surplus of pig iron, enabling Allaire to diversify into the manufacture of household goods in addition to his production of marine engines in New York.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Ships supplied with Allaire-built engines in this period included *Frank*, *New Haven*, *Rhode Island* and *Massachusetts*.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] *Massachusetts*, then the largest ship operating on Long Island Sound, was driven by a pair of beam engines.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Allaire had also accumulated considerable interest in steamships by this time.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] In 1836, a ship in which Allaire was part-owner, *William Gibbons*, ran aground and was destroyed.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] In the same year, the Howell Works furnace blew out and production there temporarily ceased.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The following year, the Panic of 1837 plunged America into a severe recession, and later that year, the steamboat *Home*, wholly owned by Allaire and largely uninsured, sank with the loss of 100 lives, damaging Allaire's reputation and leaving him short of capital.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Allaire had up until this point in his career been able to borrow to meet cash shortfalls, but with the recession affecting demand for his products, he was obliged to look elsewhere for working capital.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] In 1842, he sold shares in the Allaire Iron Works, which was incorporated for the sum of $300,000.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Shipping magnate Cornelius Vanderbilt and Allaire's brother-in-law John Haggerty were thus able to eventually gain a controlling interest in the company.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] With the capital infusion from incorporation, the Allaire Iron Works remained productive through the 1840s.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] In this period, engines were supplied for steamboats such as *Isaac Newton* in 1846, *C.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Vanderbilt* in 1847, and *Commodore* in 1848 (the names for the latter two reflecting Vanderbilt's growing influence in the company).
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Engines were also supplied for the sister ships *Bay State* and *Empire State* in 1846–47, the former of which was the fastest boat on Long Island Sound for some years.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] In 1849–50, the Allaire Works supplied the engines for two of the original four Collins Line steamers, *Pacific* and *Baltic*.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The engines for these two vessels were of the side-lever type, with *Pacific* having a 95-inch (2,400 mm) cylinder and 9-foot stroke, and *Baltic* a 96-inch (2,400 mm) cylinder and 10 foot stroke.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Both ships were to become Blue Riband winners by setting speed records for transatlantic crossings.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Allaire retired from the Presidency of the Allaire Iron Works—according to one report, through the machinations of his brother-in-law John Haggerty, who may have been scandalized by the former's marriage to a young woman 26 years his junior in 1846.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Cornelius Vanderbilt subsequently gained control of the company, appointing T.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Vanderbilt brought his own ideas to the field of marine steam engineering.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Other American marine engine manufacturers quickly followed his example, and walking beams became the preferred engine type for oceangoing American sidewheel steamships until the introduction of the much more economical surface condensing compound engine in the early 1870s.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Other ships fitted with Allaire powerplants in this period include *North Star* (1853), a transatlantic ocean liner, *St.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Lawrence* (1853), built for operation on the Great Lakes, and the Long Island Sound steamer *Plymouth Rock* (1854).
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The Allaire Iron Works made a substantial contribution to the Union cause during the American Civil War, providing the engines for at least seven warships, while at least another ten merchant ships with Allaire engines were purchased or chartered by the U.S.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] In 1861, the Allaire Works built the engines for two of the 700 ton *Unadilla* class or "90-day" gunboats, USS *Penobscot* and USS *Winona*.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The following year, the company supplied the engines for the 1,533-ton screw steamer USS *Lackawanna*, and for two of the 1,173-ton *Sassacus* class double-ended sidewheel gunboats, USS *Mackinaw* and USS *Mattabesett*.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] In 1864, the Allaire Works supplied two 100-inch (2,500 mm) cylinder, 4-foot stroke vibrating-lever engines for the 4,912-ton monitor USS *Puritan*; however delays in supply of the ship's 20-inch (510 mm) Dahlgren smoothbore cannon prevented the vessel from seeing wartime service.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The Allaire Works also supplied the engines in 1864 for the 4,215-ton *Wampanoag* class screw sloop USS *Madawaska*.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Intended to be a very fast ship, *Madawaska* was fitted with experimental vibrating-lever engines designed by Navy architect John Ericsson.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The engines proved a failure, delivering a cruising speed of only 12.73 knots, well under the specified speed of 15 knots, and they were later replaced with a more conventional power plant.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] In addition to the engines directly contracted for, the Navy also requisitioned a number of merchant steamships powered by Allaire engines and converted them into warships.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Some of these vessels had been built prior to the war, while others were built during the war and requisitioned by the Navy as they entered service.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The largest and most impressive of these ships was the 3,360-ton oceangoing sidewheel steamer *Vanderbilt*, launched in 1856, and gifted to the U.S.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Other Allaire powered ships commissioned by the Navy included *Harriet Lane*, *James Adger*, *Magnolia*, *Rhode Island*, *R.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Cuyler* and *Western World*, all built before the war, and *Fort Jackson* and the ferries *Clifton* and *Shokokon*, built during the war.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The Allaire Works also continued to produce engines for commercial vessels during the conflict, such as *City of New London*, built in 1863, and *St.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] John*, which was built in 1864 and used as a hospital ship.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Shortly after the end of hostilities, the U.S. government dumped more than a million tons of unwanted shipping onto the market, driving down prices and depriving the shipbuilding industry of new orders.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The slump lasted several years, and many ship and marine engine builders were driven to bankruptcy in this period.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] By 1867, the Allaire Iron Works had only one engine and one boiler on its books.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The company soldiered on until 1869 when Cornelius Vanderbilt sold its plant and equipment at auction, which were bought by John Roach at scrap metal prices.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Vanderbilt was wealthy enough to survive the slump, but had apparently decided to move his assets into railroads by this time.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] After the auction, the property of the Allaire Works was divided into a tombstone factory and horse stables.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Roach, one of the few marine entrepreneurs to survive and prosper in the postwar period, took the best of the Allaire Works tools, along with its best former workers, and employed them at his newly acquired plant on the East River, the Morgan Iron Works.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The following table lists merchant ships with engines supplied by the Allaire Iron Works from the company's inception in 1816 until its closure in 1867.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Names in small print preceded or followed by an arrow in the "Name" column indicate that the engine either originated from or was later installed in the ship so named.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Auxiliary steamer; first steamship to make a transatlantic crossing (albeit mostly under sail).
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] s first steam vessel powered by a compound engine.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] . and tonnage increased to 169 tons, 1836.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Made 651 trips between New York and New Haven without a breakdown.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Engine removed and converted to canal boat, 1859.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Converted to tugboat 1866; rebuilt for passenger/freight service 1880; sank 1894.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] Built for Cornelius Vanderbilt's Nicaragua Line.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] She was the first steamship to sail on Lake Nicaragua.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] The following table lists warships powered by Allaire Iron Works engines.
[src:steamboat/allaire-iron-works] This list is confined to vessels that were designed and built as warships, and does not include merchant ships commissioned into the Navy.
[src:steamboat/allan-line-royal-mail-steamers] The **Allan Shipping Line** was founded in 1819, by Captain Alexander Allan of Saltcoats, Ayrshire, trading and transporting between Scotland and Montreal, a route which quickly became synonymous with the Allan Line.
[src:steamboat/allan-line-royal-mail-steamers] By the 1830s the company had offices in Glasgow, Liverpool and Montreal.
[src:steamboat/allan-line-royal-mail-steamers] All five of Captain Allan's sons were actively involved with the business, but it was his second son, Sir Hugh Allan, who spearheaded the second generation.
[src:steamboat/allan-line-royal-mail-steamers] In 1854, Hugh launched the **Montreal Ocean Steamship Company** as part of the Allan Line, and two years later ousted Samuel Cunard to take control of the Royal Mail contract between Britain and North America.
[src:steamboat/allan-line-royal-mail-steamers] By the 1880s, the Allan Line was the world's largest privately owned shipping concern.
[src:steamboat/allan-line-royal-mail-steamers] In 1891, the company took over the State Line (founded 1872) and was often referred to as the Allan & State Line.
[src:steamboat/allan-line-royal-mail-steamers] In 1897, Andrew Allan amalgamated the various branches of the Allan shipping empire under one company, **Allan Line Steamship Company Ltd., of Glasgow**.
[src:steamboat/allan-line-royal-mail-steamers] The company by then had added offices in Boston and London.
[src:steamboat/allan-line-royal-mail-steamers] In 1917, under Sir Montagu Allan, who represented the third generation of the Allan family, the company was purchased by Canadian Pacific Steamships, and by the following year the Allan name had disappeared from commercial shipping.
[src:steamboat/allan-line-royal-mail-steamers] In 1891, the Allan Line steamship *Carthaginian* collided with the York River Line steamship *Charlotte* in the shipping channel at Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:steamboat/allan-line-royal-mail-steamers] Among those aboard *Carthaginian* was the Danish-American composer Asger Hamerik.
[src:steamboat/allan-line-royal-mail-steamers] Both ships were damaged, but neither sank.
[src:steamboat/allan-line-royal-mail-steamers] In 1905, the Allan Line ship *Parisian* was involved in a collision with the Hamburg America Line ship *Albano* off of Halifax, Nova Scotia.
[src:steamboat/allan-line-royal-mail-steamers] The Exchequer Court of Canada found *Albano* to be fully at fault, according to *Reports of Cases Relating to Maritime Law*.
[src:steamboat/allan-line-royal-mail-steamers] The case was later appealed to Canada's supreme court.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Williams*** was a military engagement during the American Civil War.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] It took place on June 15, 1864, on the Arkansas River in the Choctaw Nation (Indian Territory) which became encompassed by the State of Oklahoma.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] It is popularly termed the "only naval battle" in that landlocked state.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] It was a successful Confederate attack on the Union Army's lines of supply.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] The Confederate forces were Cherokee, Choctaw, Chickasaw and Creek Indians led by Cherokee General Stand Watie.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] The Union army was unprepared for the logistical challenges of trying to regain control of Indian Territory from the Confederate government after abandoning its forts there early in the Civil War.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] The area was largely undeveloped, and the Union did not have enough troops to control the few roads.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Groups of Indigenous peoples who sought to remain neutral in the conflict as well as the Union-allied factions had abandoned their farms because of raids by Confederate-allied factions and fled to Kansas or Missouri, seeking protection by Union army forces there.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] It was not feasible to sustain a large military operation by living off the land.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] This was demonstrated in 1862, when General William Weer led 5,000 men in the "Indian Expedition" into Indian Territory from Baxter Springs, Kansas.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Weer's troops captured a Confederate supply train at the Battle of Locust Grove.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] However, no Union supplies arrived after that, and the expedition ran short of food, ammunition and other essentials.Colonel Frederick Salomon placed Weer under arrest and assumed command of the expedition and withdrew to meet up with the supply trains.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] After the Confederate losses at the first Battle of Cabin Creek on 17 July 1863, and the Battle of Fort Smith the Union forces had essentially uncontested control of the Arkansas River between them.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] It had become feasible to resupply Union positions (e.g., Fort Gibson) in eastern Indian Territory by water instead of overland.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Previously, the Union could only supply its forces in Indian Territory by wagon train from Fort Scott, Kansas.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] The supply trains soon proved to be relatively easy targets for Confederate raiders.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Those used on the Arkansas typically, had stern-mounted paddle wheels to propel the ship, while a wood-fired boiler generated the steam that powered the wheel.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] There is anecdotal information that indicates wood was the fuel for inland steamboats.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Coal and oil became more important after the Civil War (and with the depletion of American forests near the waterways).
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] The fortunes of war had gone against the Confederate States of America by midsummer of 1863.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Union victories in the southeastern states were rapidly depleting the Confederate Army of men and supplies, neither of which was replaceable.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] The Texas units were largely withdrawn from Indian Territory, leaving only units of Native Americans (principally the Five Civilized Tribes) to defend against further Union army incursions.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] The raid was partially successful, in that the steamboat was destroyed by the action, and the cargo kept from the Union Army.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] The cargo was said to be worth $120,000.00.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] It was a propaganda victory and morale builder for the Confederates and an embarrassment to the Union.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] It had no military effect, and the monetary loss to the Union was soon dwarfed by the Confederate ambush of a very large wagon train at the Second Battle of Cabin Creek.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] A Confederate military force commanded by General Stand Watie, ambushed a Union supply steamboat on the Arkansas River in Indian Territory.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] The Confederates managed to overwhelm and disperse the Union guards, disable the vessel, loot the cargo, then destroy the vessel before withdrawing.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Although the encounter left unchanged the American Civil War's outcome, it was a morale-booster for the rebel supporters and reportedly helped the Native American allies of the Confederacy prolong a stalemate in the territory until war's end in 1865.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Williams* was proceeding up the Arkansas River from Fort Smith to Fort Gibson.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Its cargo was primarily commissary goods and food for the Native American refugees who had recently returned from their exile in Kansas and Missouri, hoping to recover their homes and farms they had abandoned in Indian Territory.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] A token guard–one officer (Lieutenant Horace A.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Cook), a sergeant and 24 privates from the 12th Regiment Kansas Volunteer Infantry—was aboard.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] As the steamboat rounded a bend at Pleasant Bluff, located just below the mouth of the Canadian River near the present-day town of Tamaha in Haskell County, Oklahoma, a Confederate force of about 400 men, commanded by Colonel Stand Watie, opened fire with cannon and small arms.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] The artillery was particularly effective.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] The smokestack, pilot house and boiler were hit, disabling the vessel.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] The captain and crew managed to ground the boat on the north bank of the river, opposite the Confederate position.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] The guardsmen opened fire, even though steam from the boiler enveloped the deck.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Cook wanted to hold off the Confederates until Union reinforcements arrived, but he saw the ship's captain and the sergeant sailing the steamboat's yawl across the river toward the enemy position.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Realizing that the Confederates would use that to attack the steamboat in force, he ordered his surviving men to abandon ship.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Cook and his men withdrew, located a Union army camp nearby and reported the ambush.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Meanwhile, Watie's men boarded the abandoned steamboat and managed to tow it to a sandbar on the south side of the river.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] They hastily unloaded the cargo onto the bar, then began to load as much as possible on their horses.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Watie knew that his command was depleted.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] So many men had left to carry their booty home, that his artillery was in jeopardy.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] One article stated that the boat carried a thousand barrels of flour and fifteen tons of bacon.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] According to another account the cargo included a load of men's dress clothing, with top hats, dinner jackets with tails, fancy trousers and spats.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Allegedly, Watie's men wore these as their uniforms thereafter.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] A more lethal part of the cargo was 400 Sharps rifles and 600 new revolvers.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Later that day, Colonel John Ritchie and 200 men from the 2nd Regiment of the Indian Home Guard arrived from the Union camp and began to fire on the Confederates.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] The river began to rise, and after Ritchie's arrival, covered the sandbar and the remainder of the cargo.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] The rising water even carried away part of the flour and bacon that had been moved to higher ground.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Watie set the steamboat afire and withdrew from the scene with his troops.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Shortly afterward, he received official news of his promotion to brigadier general, effective May 10, 1864.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] It is reported that many of the Confederate troops took their booty and disappeared, thereby hampering General Watie's next operation.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] On July 17, 1864, Watie reported the results of the encounter to his superior, General Cooper.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] He noted that he was sending six prisoners from the steamboat.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] He also stated that four of the Union men were killed.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] To the Confederates, especially those in the Indian Territory, Watie's success was primarily symbolic.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] However, the outcome had no meaningful effect on the outcome of the American Civil War.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] It was a morale booster and provided some much needed supplies in the local theater of operation.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] To the Union, it emphasized the risk of moving supplies via river transport and the need to control the few roads.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] To local Confederate supporters, almost desperate for favorable war news in 1864, it was a time for rejoicing.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Stand Watie's reputation as a successful guerilla raider was enhanced.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] The action has been commemorated by a marker erected by the Oklahoma Historical Society in Stigler, Oklahoma, in 1995.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Some present-day Oklahomans like to refer to this encounter as "the only naval battle ever fought in Oklahoma".
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Congress authorized publication of the official war records of both armies of the Civil War.
[src:steamboat/ambush-of-the-steamboat-j-r-williams] Colonel Watie's official dispatches, and those of his commanding officer regarding this battle were published in 1891.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] A **steamboat** is a boat that is propelled primarily by steam power, typically driving propellers or paddlewheels.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The term *steamboat* is used to refer to small steam-powered vessels working on lakes, rivers, and in short-sea shipping.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The development of the steamboat led to the larger steamship, which is a seaworthy and often ocean-going ship.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Steamboats sometimes use the prefix designation **SS**, **S.S.** or **S/S** (for 'Screw Steamer') or **PS** (for 'Paddle Steamer'); however, these designations are most often used for steamships.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The first steamboat designs used Newcomen steam engines.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] These engines were large, heavy, and produced little power, which resulted in an unfavorable power-to-weight ratio.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The heavy weight of the Newcomen engine required a structurally strong boat, and the reciprocating motion of the engine beam required a complicated mechanism to produce propulsion.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] James Watt's design improvements increased the efficiency of the steam engine, improving the power-to-weight ratio, and created an engine capable of rotary motion by using a double-acting cylinder which injected steam at each end of the piston stroke to move the piston back and forth.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The rotary steam engine simplified the mechanism required to turn a paddle wheel to propel a boat.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Despite the improved efficiency and rotary motion, the power-to-weight ratio of Boulton and Watt steam engine was still low.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The high-pressure steam engine was the development that made the steamboat practical.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] It had a high power-to-weight ratio and was fuel efficient.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] High pressure engines were made possible by improvements in the design of boilers and engine components so that they could withstand internal pressure, although boiler explosions were common due to lack of instrumentation like pressure gauges.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Attempts at making high-pressure engines had to wait until the expiration of the Boulton and Watt patent in 1800.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Shortly thereafter high-pressure engines by Richard Trevithick and Oliver Evans were introduced.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The compound steam engine became widespread in the late 19th century.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Compounding uses exhaust steam from a high pressure cylinder to a lower pressure cylinder and greatly improves efficiency.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] With compound engines it was possible for trans ocean steamers to carry less coal than freight.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Compound steam engine powered ships enabled a great increase in international trade.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The most efficient steam engine used for marine propulsion is the steam turbine.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] It was developed near the end of the 19th century and was used throughout the 20th century.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] An apocryphal story from 1851 attributes the earliest steamboat to Denis Papin for a boat he built in 1705.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Papin was an early innovator in steam power and the inventor of the steam digester, the first pressure cooker, which played an important role in James Watt's steam experiments.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] However, Papin's boat was not steam-powered but powered by hand-cranked paddles.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] A steamboat was described and patented by English physician John Allen in 1729.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] In 1736, Jonathan Hulls was granted a patent in England for a Newcomen engine-powered steamboat (using a pulley instead of a beam, and a pawl and ratchet to obtain rotary motion), but it was the improvement in steam engines by James Watt that made the concept feasible.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] William Henry of Lancaster, Pennsylvania, having learned of Watt's engine on a visit to England, made his own engine, and put it in a boat.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The boat sank, and while Henry made an improved model, he did not appear to have much success, though he may have inspired others.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The first steam-powered ship, *Pyroscaphe*, was a paddle steamer powered by a double-acting steam engine; it was built in France in 1783 by Marquis Claude de Jouffroy and his colleagues as an improvement of an earlier attempt, the 1776 *Palmipède*.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] At its first demonstration on 15 July 1783, *Pyroscaphe* travelled upstream on the river Saône for some fifteen minutes before the engine failed.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Presumably this was easily repaired as the boat is said to have made several such journeys.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Following this, De Jouffroy attempted to get the government interested in his work, but for political reasons was instructed that he would have to build another version on the Seine in Paris.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] De Jouffroy did not have the funds for this, and, following the events of the French revolution, work on the project was discontinued after he left the country.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Similar boats were made in 1785 by John Fitch in Philadelphia and William Symington in Dumfries, Scotland.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Fitch successfully trialled his boat in 1787, and in 1788, he began operating a regular commercial service along the Delaware River between Philadelphia and Burlington, New Jersey, carrying as many as 30 passengers.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] This boat could typically make 7 to 8 miles per hour (11 to 13 km/h) and travelled more than 2,000 miles (3,200 km) during its short length of service.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The Fitch steamboat was not a commercial success, as this travel route was adequately covered by relatively good wagon roads.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The following year, a second boat made 30-mile (48 km) excursions, and in 1790, a third boat ran a series of trials on the Delaware River before patent disputes dissuaded Fitch from continuing.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Meanwhile, Patrick Miller of Dalswinton, near Dumfries, Scotland, had developed double-hulled boats propelled by manually cranked paddle wheels placed between the hulls, even attempting to interest various European governments in a giant warship version, 246 feet (75 m) long.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Miller sent King Gustav III of Sweden an actual small-scale version, 100 feet (30 m) long, called *Experiment*.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Miller then engaged engineer William Symington to build his patent steam engine that drove a stern-mounted paddle wheel in a boat in 1785.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The boat was successfully tried out on Dalswinton Loch in 1788 and was followed by a larger steamboat the next year.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The boat was built by Alexander Hart at Grangemouth to Symington's design with a vertical cylinder engine and crosshead transmitting power to a crank driving the paddlewheels.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Trials on the River Carron in June 1801 were successful and included towing sloops from the river Forth up the Carron and thence along the Forth and Clyde Canal.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] In 1801, Symington patented a horizontal steam engine directly linked to a crank.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] He got support from Lord Dundas to build a second steamboat, which became famous as the *Charlotte Dundas*, named in honour of Lord Dundas's daughter.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Symington designed a new hull around his powerful horizontal engine, with the crank driving a large paddle wheel in a central upstand in the hull, aimed at avoiding damage to the canal banks.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The new boat was 56 ft (17.1 m) long, 18 ft (5.5 m) wide and 8 ft (2.4 m) depth, with a wooden hull.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The boat was built by John Allan and the engine by the Carron Company.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The first sailing was on the canal in Glasgow on 4 January 1803, with Lord Dundas and a few of his relatives and friends on board.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The crowd were pleased with what they saw, but Symington wanted to make improvements and another more ambitious trial was made on 28 March.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] On this occasion, the *Charlotte Dundas* towed two 70 ton barges 30 km (almost 20 miles) along the Forth and Clyde Canal to Glasgow, and despite "a strong breeze right ahead" that stopped all other canal boats it took only nine and a quarter hours, giving an average speed of about 3 km/h (2 mph).
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The *Charlotte Dundas* was the first practical steamboat, in that it demonstrated the practicality of steam power for ships, and was the first to be followed by continuous development of steamboats.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The American Robert Fulton was present at the trials of the *Charlotte Dundas* and was intrigued by the potential of the steamboat.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] While working in France, he corresponded with and was helped by the Scottish engineer Henry Bell, who may have given him the first model of his working steamboat.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Fulton designed his own steamboat, which sailed along the River Seine in 1803.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] In May 1804, John Stevens would design and build a steamboat named the Little Juliana after his eldest daughter Juliana, it was the first powered vessel with a screw propeller propulsion system.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Fulton later obtained a Boulton and Watt steam engine, shipped to America, where his first proper steamship was built in 1807, *North River Steamboat* (later known as *Clermont*), which carried passengers between New York City and Albany, New York.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] *Clermont* was able to make the 150-mile (240 km) trip in 32 hours.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The steamboat was powered by a Boulton and Watt engine and was capable of long-distance travel.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] It was the first commercially successful steamboat, transporting passengers along the Hudson River.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Stevens began operation of the *Phoenix*, which used a high-pressure engine in combination with a low-pressure condensing engine.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The first steamboats powered only by high pressure were the *Aetna* and *Pennsylvania*, designed and built by Oliver Evans.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] In October 1811 a ship designed by John Stevens, *Juliana*, would operate as the first steam-powered ferry between Hoboken and New York City.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] Stevens' ship was engineered as a twin-screw-driven steamboat in juxtaposition to *Clermont*'s Boulton and Watt engine.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The design was a modification of Stevens' prior paddle steamer *Phoenix*, the first steamship to successfully navigate the open ocean in its route from Hoboken to Philadelphia.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] In 1812, Henry Bell's PS *Comet* was inaugurated.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The steamboat was the first commercial passenger service in Europe and sailed along the River Clyde in Scotland.
[src:steamboat/steamboat-p01] The *Margery*, launched in Dumbarton in 1814, in January 1815 became the first steamboat on the River Thames, much to the amazement of Londoners.
